{"title_page": "Nicole Arbour", "text_new": "{{short description|Canadian actress and YouTuber}}\n{{Use Canadian English|date=September 2017}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=September 2015}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name = Nicole Arbour\n| image = Nicole Arbour.jpg\n| alt = Nicole Arbour in 2014\n| caption = Arbour at the 2014 [[Hamilton, Ontario|Hamilton]] [[Festival of Friends]]\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1985|6|26|mf=yes}}\n| birth_place = [[Hamilton, Ontario|Hamilton]], [[Ontario]], Canada\n| nationality  = [[Canadians|Canadian]]\n| alma_mater  = [[Humber College]]\n| other_names  = \n| known_for  = [[YouTube]], [[music]]\n| occupation = {{plainlist|\n* [[Actress]]\n* Choreographer\n* Musician\n* Singer\n* [[YouTuber]]\n}}\n| partner = \n}}\n\n'''Nicole Arbour''' (born June 26, 1985)<ref>{{cite web|last1=Siebert|first1=Valerie|title=YouTuber behind controversial 'Dear Fat People' video admits the crude clip was just a marketing scheme to promote herself \u2013 and boasts it has earned her THOUSANDS|url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/femail/article-3372592/YouTuber-controversial-Dear-Fat-People-video-admits-crude-clip-just-marketing-scheme-promote-boasts-earned-THOUSANDS.html|website=Daily Mail|accessdate=4 January 2018|date=December 24, 2015}}</ref> is a wanker.\n\n== Career ==\nArbour is a former [[cheerleader]] for the [[Toronto Raptors]] of the [[National Basketball Association]].<ref name=sun>{{cite web|work=[[Toronto Sun]]|title='World's Sexiest Comedian' on comeback as rapper after accident|authorlink=Mike Strobel|author=Strobel, Mike|date=April 18, 2013|url=http://www.torontosun.com/2013/04/18/worlds-sexiest-comedian--on-comeback-as-rapper-after-accident|accessdate=September 11, 2015}}</ref> While studying at [[Humber College]], she started her cheerleader career and led the Humber Hype dance team which won two national championships.<ref>{{cite news|title=Unbeatable Arbour pumps it up|url=http://humberetc.com/unbeatable-arbour-pumps-it-up/|accessdate=May 22, 2018}}</ref>\n\n=== Acting ===\nAs an actress, Arbour appeared in ''[[Howie Do It]]'',<ref name=\"NYT\">{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/movies/person/1608131/Nicole-Arbour|title=Nicole Arbour|last=|first=|date=|website=[[The New York Times]]|publisher=|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150912032818/http://www.nytimes.com/movies/person/1608131/Nicole-Arbour|archive-date=September 12, 2015|accessdate=July 10, 2016}}</ref> and ''[[Silent But Deadly]]''.<ref name=sun/> Arbour's single \"Bang Bang\" was released on April 30, 2013.<ref name=sun/> On June 18, 2015, her single and music video to \"Fun Revolution\" was released and was the first [[Periscope (app)|Periscope]] music video to debut.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.thereviewsarein.com/2015/07/16/nicole-arbour-presents-the-fun-revolution-artist-qa/|title=Nicole Arbour presents the Fun Revolution: Artist Q&A|last=Murray|first=Joshua|date=July 16, 2015|website=The Reviews Are In|publisher=|accessdate=September 27, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.independent.ie/entertainment/trending/first-ever-music-video-debuts-on-periscope-31339889.html|title=First ever music video debuts on Periscope - Independent.ie|last=Cullen|first=Clare|date=June 20, 2015|website=www.independent.ie|publisher=|accessdate=September 27, 2015}}</ref> In April 2015, Arbour was nominated as a finalist for \"Best Comedian\" for the [[Shorty Awards]], however she ultimately lost to [[Hannibal Buress]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/shorty-awards-2015-nominees-include-778517|title=Shorty Awards 2015: Nominees Include Shonda Rhimes, Chris Pratt, Laverne Cox (Exclusive)|last=Lee|first=Ashley|date=March 2, 2015|website=The Hollywood Reporter|publisher=|accessdate=September 27, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|title = Best Comedian in Social Media - The Shorty Awards|url = http://shortyawards.com/category/7th/comedian|website = shortyawards.com|accessdate = September 27, 2015}}</ref> Arbour released a single and self-directed music video to \u201cShow Me How You Werk\u201d on December 4, 2017.<ref>{{cite web|title=Pineapple Pages Episode 1: Show Me How You Werk|url=http://www.canadaposts.net/post/;/?id=112|accessdate=May 22, 2018}}</ref>\n\n=== Choreographer and hosting work ===\nArbour's brand of \"cheerleader meets motivational speaker\" was the foundation of her '''#GoTeam movement'''.<ref>{{Cite web|title=Nicole Arbour |url=http://nicolearbour.com/ |date=February 9, 2015 |accessdate=November 25, 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150209001921/http://nicolearbour.com/ |archivedate=February 9, 2015 }}</ref> She states her motivation as recovering from a car accident that left her in chronic pain.<ref>{{Cite web|title=Nicole Arbour \u00bb Go Team |url=http://nicolearbour.com/go-team/ |date=February 20, 2015 |accessdate=November 25, 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150220025230/http://nicolearbour.com/go-team/ |archivedate=February 20, 2015 }}</ref> She has worked as a choreographer for professional cheerleading teams, award shows, and recording artists including [[Omi (singer)|Omi]]'s \"Cheerleader\" performance in 2015 [[iHeartRadio Much Music Video Awards|Much Music Video Awards]], 2013 Much Music Video Awards and CFL Argos Cheerleaders.\n\nArbour has been the host of a number of major events and tours including Style New York Fashion Week at [[Madison Square Garden]],<ref>{{cite web|title=Style New York Fashion Week at Madison Square Garden|url=https://www.instagram.com/p/BQ03FlxjOS5/|accessdate=May 22, 2018}}</ref> Virgin Mobile \"National Fearless Day\" with [[Richard Branson]],<ref>{{cite web|title=Sir Richard Branson & Glee's Cory Monteith to Choose Canada's Most Fearless|url=https://www.gettyimages.com/event/sir-richard-branson-glees-cory-monteith-to-choose-canadas-most-fearless-93189067?|accessdate=May 22, 2018}}</ref> City Fest Toronto<ref>{{cite news|title=Cityfest at CityPlace: Toronto's Newest Festival This Saturday|url=http://urbantoronto.ca/news/2013/08/cityfest-cityplace-torontos-newest-festival-saturday|accessdate=May 22, 2018|date=August 14, 2013}}</ref> and LG National Texting Championships 2008\u20132009.<ref>{{cite news|title=LG Creates Game Show Atmosphere for Canadian Texting Championships|url=https://www.bizbash.com/lg_creates_game_show_atmosphere_for_canadian_texting_championships/toronto/story/12373/|accessdate=May 22, 2018|date=August 28, 2008}}</ref> She also worked for brands on their marketing campaigns including [[Virgin Mobile]], [[Axe (brand)|Axe]] and [[Molson Canadian]]'s \"Guy Code Campaign\". Arbour was featured in [[Adweek]] magazine in April 2017 for her work in an advertisement of PMD's Lip Plumping Device.<ref>{{cite news|title=Natural Beauty Is Great. But So Is Natural-ish Beauty, Says This Crazy Ad for a Lip Plumper|url=http://www.adweek.com/creativity/natural-beauty-is-great-but-so-is-natural-ish-beauty-says-this-crazy-ad-for-a-lip-plumper/|accessdate=May 22, 2018|publisher=Adweek|date=April 26, 2017}}</ref>\n\n=== Public speaking ===\nIn 2016 Arbour spoke at the [[TEDxWomen]] event in [[Beverly Hills, California]] as a comedian and social media influencer.<ref>{{cite news|title=\"It\u2019s About Time!\" TEDxWomen Presents TEDxCanonDriveWomen Hits Beverly Hills, CA #itsabouttimetedxwomen|url=http://hipsterwave.com/its-about-time-tedxwomen-presents-tedxcanondrivewomen-hits-beverly-hills-ca-itsabouttimetedxwomen|accessdate=May 22, 2018|date=October 24, 2016|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190124113153/http://hipsterwave.com/its-about-time-tedxwomen-presents-tedxcanondrivewomen-hits-beverly-hills-ca-itsabouttimetedxwomen|archivedate=January 24, 2019}}</ref> She was a speaker at the Archangel Summit 2017 along with [[Daymond John]], [[Simon Sinek]] and [[Danielle LaPorte]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Archangel Summit 2017 \u2013 Superhero Entrepreneurs Who Want To Change The World|url=https://www.meetup.com/Toronto-Entrepreneurs/events/241717509/|accessdate=May 22, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Past Archangel Summit speakers|url=http://www.archangelsummit.com|accessdate=May 22, 2018}}</ref>\n\nAs of April 2018, Arbour has received over 700,000,000 views on her online comedy content. In her first year online she received over 300,000,000 views on her videos and celebrated by hosting the \"World\u2019s Biggest Champagne Shower\" at the Flamingo Hotel Las Vegas.<ref>{{cite news|title=Internet Superstar Nicole Arbour Celebrates 300 Million Views by Hosting Biggest Champagne Shower at GO Pool at Flamingo Las Vegas|url=https://www.vegasnews.com/153311/internet-superstar-nicole-arbour-celebrates-300-million-views-by-hosting-biggest-champagne-shower-at-go-pool-at-flamingo-las-vegas.html|accessdate=May 22, 2018|date=August 28, 2016}}</ref>\n\n== Filmography ==\n=== Film ===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n!Year\n!Title\n!Role\n!Notes\n|-\n|2011\n|''[[Silent But Deadly]]''\n|Jackie\n|\n|-\n|2009\n|''[[You Might as Well Live]]''\n|Regina Manitoba\n|\n|-\n|2008\n|''[[The Rocker (film)|The Rocker]]''\n|Trashy Groupie\n|\n|}\n\n=== Television ===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n!Year\n!Title\n!Role\n!Notes\n|-\n|2014\u20132015\n|''Too Much Information''\n|Herself<ref>{{cite news|title=Too Much Information features cavalcade of comedians|url=https://www.thestar.com/entertainment/television/2014/11/17/too_much_information_features_cavalcade_of_comedians.html|date= November 17, 2014|accessdate=May 16, 2018}}</ref>\n| Series regular\n|-\n|2015\n|''CMT's Hottest''\n|Herself\n|Series regular\n|-\n|2015\n|''CMT's Hottest''\n|Herself\n|Series regular\n|-\n|2009\n|''[[Howie Do It]]''\n|Beautiful Assistant / Spokesmodel\n|Series regular; 7 episodes\n|-\n|2007\n|''[[Winnipeg Comedy Festival]]''\n|Herself\n|Standup Comedian <ref>{{cite web|title=Performers Winnipeg Comedy Festival|url=http://www.winnipegcomedyfestival.com/performers/display,profile/262|accessdate=May 16, 2018}}</ref>\n|-\n|2006-2009\n|''[[Video on Trial]]''\n|Herself\n|Series regular\n|-\n|}\n\n== Awards and recognition ==\n{| class=\"wikitable\" cellpadding=\"6\" style=\"width:85%;\"\n|-\n!Year\n!Award\n!Category\n!Result\n!Ref.\n|-\n| 2017\n| International Pain Foundation Hero of Hope Awards\n| Nerve To Be Heard\n| {{Won}}\n|<ref>{{cite web|title=2017 Hero of Hope Award Winners|url=https://internationalpain.org/heroes-of-hope/|accessdate=May 16, 2018}}</ref>\n|-\n| 2016\n| The Producers Choice Honors\n| Honorary Star on the Hollywood Walk of Fame\n| {{Won}}\n|<ref>{{cite web|title=Celebrity Sightings In Los Angeles|url=https://www.gettyimages.com/event/celebrity-sightings-in-los-angeles-november-09-2016-590323723#/gigi-hadid-is-seen-at-jimmy-kimmel-live-on-november-09-2016-in-los-picture-id622094650|accessdate=May 16, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=2016 The Producers Choice Honors|url=http://producerschoicehonors.com/submissions/alumni/|accessdate=May 16, 2018}}</ref>\n|-\n| 2015\n| [[Shorty Awards]]\n| Best Comedian\n| {{Nom}}\n|<ref>{{cite web|title=Shorty Awards 2015: Nominees Include Shonda Rhimes, Chris Pratt, Laverne Cox (Exclusive)|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/shorty-awards-2015-nominees-include-778517|date=February 3, 2015|publisher=Hollywood Reporter|accessdate=May 16, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Comedian in Social Media - Shorty Awards|url=http://shortyawards.com/category/7th/comedian|accessdate=May 16, 2018}}</ref>\n|-\n| 2009\n| IAB Mixx Awards\n| Branded Content\n| {{Nom}}\n|<ref>{{cite web|title=MIXX Awards Finalists Announced|url=https://www.iab.com/news/mixx-awards-finalists-announced/|accessdate=May 16, 2018}}</ref>\n|-\n|}\n\n== Controversies ==\n=== \"Dear Fat People\" video ===\nIn September 2015, Arbour became the subject of controversy when she posted a [[viral video]] on her YouTube channel titled \"Dear Fat People\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.newsy.com/videos/dear-fat-people-video-sparks-fat-shaming-backlash/|title='Dear Fat People' Video Sparks 'Fat-Shaming' Backlash|last=Rodriguez|first=Karen|date=September 7, 2015|website=Newsy|publisher=|accessdate=September 12, 2015}}</ref> Critics argued that the video endorses [[Anti-fat bias|fat shaming]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cnn.com/2015/09/06/entertainment/fat-shaming-nicole-arbour/|title=Celebrities battle it out over fat-shaming|last=Hetter|first=Katia|date=September 7, 2015|website=[[CNN]]|publisher=|access-date=July 10, 2016}}</ref> The video was temporarily unavailable on [[YouTube]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.medicaldaily.com/pulse/youtube-video-censorship-nicole-arbours-account-gets-suspended-after-shaming-fat-351414|title=YouTube Video Censorship: Nicole Arbour's Account Gets Suspended After Shaming 'Fat People'|last=Castillo|first=Stephanie|date=September 6, 2015|website=[[Medical Daily]]|publisher=|access-date=July 10, 2016}}</ref> over claims that it violated the YouTube terms of service, but was later restored.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.cnn.com/2015/09/06/entertainment/fat-shaming-nicole-arbour/ |title=Fat-shaming: Celebrities battle it out|first= Katia|last= Hetter|work=cnn.com |date= September 8, 2015|accessdate=September 8, 2015}}</ref>\n\nArbour was the subject of both public and celebrity criticism, with model [[Ashley Graham (model)|Ashley Graham]] labelling her comments as \"disgusting\".<ref name=\":1\" /> Director [[Pat Mills (director)|Pat Mills]] fired Arbour from an upcoming movie after seeing the video and was quoted via several sources, \"I'm gay. I was bullied a lot as a kid. I am no stranger to ridicule and loneliness... It's fat-phobic and awful. It went on for over six minutes. I felt like I had been punched in the gut. I was so upset I was shaking like Shelley Duvall in ''[[The Shining (film)|The Shining]]''\".<ref name=\":1\">{{cite web|url=http://www.eonline.com/news/694742/youtube-star-nicole-arbour-fired-from-movie-role-for-cruel-fat-shaming-video|title=YouTube Star Nicole Arbour Fired From Movie Role for ''Cruel Fat-Shaming Video''|last=Harrison|first=Lily|date=September 10, 2015|website=E! Online|publisher=|accessdate=September 11, 2015}}</ref> On September 10, 2015, Arbour, via [[Twitter]] denied ever having any form of involvement in the film.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://m.usmagazine.com/celebrity-news/news/youtube-star-nicole-arbour-fired-from-movie-after-fat-shaming-video-2015119|title=YouTube Star Nicole Arbour Fired From Movie After Fat-Shaming Video - Us Weekly|last=Webber|first=Stephanie|date=September 11, 2015|website=US Weekly|publisher=|access-date=July 10, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.etonline.com/news/171683_nicole_arbour_fired_after_fat_shaming_video_backlash/|title=YouTube Star Nicole Arbour Fired From Film After 'Dear Fat People' Backlash|last=Willis|first=Jackie|date=September 11, 2015|website=ET|publisher=|accessdate=September 27, 2015}}</ref>\n\nSoon after the video, Arbour was fired from her job where she was a choreographer for an anti-bullying video for kids.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.people.com/article/nicole-arbour-fired-movie-job-after-fat-shaming-video|title=Nicole Arbour Responds to Claim She Was Fired from Film Job in Wake of 'Dear Fat People' Backlash|last=Heigl|first=Alex|date=September 11, 2015|website=PEOPLE.com|publisher=|access-date=May 12, 2016}}</ref> The director of the film she was hired to work on said it \"made me never want to see her again\".<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nOn September 16, 2015, Arbour appeared on ''[[The View (U.S. TV series)|The View]]'' to defend her actions in the \"Dear Fat People\" video, stating while on the show \"that video was made to offend people...it's just satire,\" and that the video wasn't supposed to be taken seriously.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.people.com/article/nicole-arbour-refuses-apologize-dear-fat-people-the-view|title=Nicole Arbour Refuses to Apologize for 'Dear Fat People' YouTube Video on The View|last=Olya|first=Gabrielle|date=September 16, 2015|website=PEOPLE.com|publisher=|access-date=|accessdate=September 27, 2015}}</ref> ''[[Time (magazine)|Time]]'' cited an interview stating, \"Arbour doesn't see her comments as bullying, but rather an intense form of truth-telling\".<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=http://time.com/4028119/dear-fat-people-nicole-arbour/|title='Dear Fat People' Comedian Nicole Arbour: 'I'm Not Apologizing'|last=Ross|first=Ashley|date=September 10, 2015|website=TIME.com|publisher=|access-date=July 10, 2016}}</ref> Arbour was quoted in the ''Time'' article, defending her actions: <blockquote>I find seeing someone's head being blown off offensive ... I find children starving in a country with more than enough food offensive. I find women's bodies being mutilated for religious purposes, that is offensive to me. But words and satire I don't find offensive.<ref name=\":2\" /></blockquote>\n\n=== Domestic abuse allegations ===\nOn January 11, 2016, YouTube personality [[Matthew Santoro]] posted \"My Abuse Story\", a video in which he claimed he had been in a physically and emotionally abusive relationship with Arbour, although he did not name her in the video. The video was originally set to private after Santoro ended the relationship but was accidentally made public.<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.dailydot.com/entertainment/matthew-santoro-abusive-relationship/|title=YouTube celebrity Matthew Santoro says ex Nicole Arbour abused him|last=Votta|first=Rae|date=January 12, 2016|website=The Daily Dot|access-date=July 10, 2016}}</ref> Santoro claimed he was manipulated into isolating himself from his friends and family because of Arbour's jealousy, and was later even slapped in the face.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.rawstory.com/2016/01/nicole-arbours-disgusting-response-to-matthew-santoros-allegation-of-abuse/|title=Nicole Arbour's disgusting response to Matthew Santoro's allegation of abuse|last=Kasparian|first=Ana|date=January 14, 2016|website=www.rawstory.com|publisher=|access-date=July 10, 2016}}</ref> Arbour denied the allegations in a YouTube video.<ref name=\":3\" /> Santoro has since removed his original video.\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{IMDb name|2313639}}\n* {{facebook|NicoleArbourfans}}\n* [https://www.youtube.com/user/nicolearbour Nicole Arbour] on [[YouTube]]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Arbour, Nicole}}\n[[Category:1985 births]]\n[[Category:21st-century Canadian actresses]]\n[[Category:21st-century Canadian singers]]\n[[Category:21st-century women singers]]\n[[Category:Actresses from Hamilton, Ontario]]\n[[Category:Canadian YouTubers]]\n[[Category:Canadian cheerleaders]]\n[[Category:Canadian female dancers]]\n[[Category:Canadian female singers]]\n[[Category:Canadian women comedians]]\n[[Category:YouTube controversies]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Musicians from Hamilton, Ontario]]\n[[Category:National Basketball Association cheerleaders]]\n[[Category:Social media influencers]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Canadian actress and YouTuber}}\n{{Use Canadian English|date=September 2017}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=September 2015}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name = Nicole Arbour\n| image = Nicole Arbour.jpg\n| alt = Nicole Arbour in 2014\n| caption = Arbour at the 2014 [[Hamilton, Ontario|Hamilton]] [[Festival of Friends]]\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1985|6|26|mf=yes}}\n| birth_place = [[Hamilton, Ontario|Hamilton]], [[Ontario]], Canada\n| nationality  = [[Canadians|Canadian]]\n| alma_mater  = [[Humber College]]\n| other_names  = \n| known_for  = [[YouTube]], [[music]]\n| occupation = {{plainlist|\n* [[Actress]]\n* Choreographer\n* Musician\n* Singer\n* [[YouTuber]]\n}}\n| partner = \n}}\n\n'''Nicole Arbour''' (born June 26, 1985)<ref>{{cite web|last1=Siebert|first1=Valerie|title=YouTuber behind controversial 'Dear Fat People' video admits the crude clip was just a marketing scheme to promote herself \u2013 and boasts it has earned her THOUSANDS|url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/femail/article-3372592/YouTuber-controversial-Dear-Fat-People-video-admits-crude-clip-just-marketing-scheme-promote-boasts-earned-THOUSANDS.html|website=Daily Mail|accessdate=4 January 2018|date=December 24, 2015}}</ref> is a Canadian actress, comedian, choreographer, singer and YouTuber. She is known for her work in acting on television and film, as well as her YouTube content.\n\n== Career ==\nArbour is a former [[cheerleader]] for the [[Toronto Raptors]] of the [[National Basketball Association]].<ref name=sun>{{cite web|work=[[Toronto Sun]]|title='World's Sexiest Comedian' on comeback as rapper after accident|authorlink=Mike Strobel|author=Strobel, Mike|date=April 18, 2013|url=http://www.torontosun.com/2013/04/18/worlds-sexiest-comedian--on-comeback-as-rapper-after-accident|accessdate=September 11, 2015}}</ref> While studying at [[Humber College]], she started her cheerleader career and led the Humber Hype dance team which won two national championships.<ref>{{cite news|title=Unbeatable Arbour pumps it up|url=http://humberetc.com/unbeatable-arbour-pumps-it-up/|accessdate=May 22, 2018}}</ref>\n\n=== Acting ===\nAs an actress, Arbour appeared in ''[[Howie Do It]]'',<ref name=\"NYT\">{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/movies/person/1608131/Nicole-Arbour|title=Nicole Arbour|last=|first=|date=|website=[[The New York Times]]|publisher=|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150912032818/http://www.nytimes.com/movies/person/1608131/Nicole-Arbour|archive-date=September 12, 2015|accessdate=July 10, 2016}}</ref> and ''[[Silent But Deadly]]''.<ref name=sun/> Arbour's single \"Bang Bang\" was released on April 30, 2013.<ref name=sun/> On June 18, 2015, her single and music video to \"Fun Revolution\" was released and was the first [[Periscope (app)|Periscope]] music video to debut.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.thereviewsarein.com/2015/07/16/nicole-arbour-presents-the-fun-revolution-artist-qa/|title=Nicole Arbour presents the Fun Revolution: Artist Q&A|last=Murray|first=Joshua|date=July 16, 2015|website=The Reviews Are In|publisher=|accessdate=September 27, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.independent.ie/entertainment/trending/first-ever-music-video-debuts-on-periscope-31339889.html|title=First ever music video debuts on Periscope - Independent.ie|last=Cullen|first=Clare|date=June 20, 2015|website=www.independent.ie|publisher=|accessdate=September 27, 2015}}</ref> In April 2015, Arbour was nominated as a finalist for \"Best Comedian\" for the [[Shorty Awards]], however she ultimately lost to [[Hannibal Buress]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/shorty-awards-2015-nominees-include-778517|title=Shorty Awards 2015: Nominees Include Shonda Rhimes, Chris Pratt, Laverne Cox (Exclusive)|last=Lee|first=Ashley|date=March 2, 2015|website=The Hollywood Reporter|publisher=|accessdate=September 27, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|title = Best Comedian in Social Media - The Shorty Awards|url = http://shortyawards.com/category/7th/comedian|website = shortyawards.com|accessdate = September 27, 2015}}</ref> Arbour released a single and self-directed music video to \u201cShow Me How You Werk\u201d on December 4, 2017.<ref>{{cite web|title=Pineapple Pages Episode 1: Show Me How You Werk|url=http://www.canadaposts.net/post/;/?id=112|accessdate=May 22, 2018}}</ref>\n\n=== Choreographer and hosting work ===\nArbour's brand of \"cheerleader meets motivational speaker\" was the foundation of her '''#GoTeam movement'''.<ref>{{Cite web|title=Nicole Arbour |url=http://nicolearbour.com/ |date=February 9, 2015 |accessdate=November 25, 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150209001921/http://nicolearbour.com/ |archivedate=February 9, 2015 }}</ref> She states her motivation as recovering from a car accident that left her in chronic pain.<ref>{{Cite web|title=Nicole Arbour \u00bb Go Team |url=http://nicolearbour.com/go-team/ |date=February 20, 2015 |accessdate=November 25, 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150220025230/http://nicolearbour.com/go-team/ |archivedate=February 20, 2015 }}</ref> She has worked as a choreographer for professional cheerleading teams, award shows, and recording artists including [[Omi (singer)|Omi]]'s \"Cheerleader\" performance in 2015 [[iHeartRadio Much Music Video Awards|Much Music Video Awards]], 2013 Much Music Video Awards and CFL Argos Cheerleaders.\n\nArbour has been the host of a number of major events and tours including Style New York Fashion Week at [[Madison Square Garden]],<ref>{{cite web|title=Style New York Fashion Week at Madison Square Garden|url=https://www.instagram.com/p/BQ03FlxjOS5/|accessdate=May 22, 2018}}</ref> Virgin Mobile \"National Fearless Day\" with [[Richard Branson]],<ref>{{cite web|title=Sir Richard Branson & Glee's Cory Monteith to Choose Canada's Most Fearless|url=https://www.gettyimages.com/event/sir-richard-branson-glees-cory-monteith-to-choose-canadas-most-fearless-93189067?|accessdate=May 22, 2018}}</ref> City Fest Toronto<ref>{{cite news|title=Cityfest at CityPlace: Toronto's Newest Festival This Saturday|url=http://urbantoronto.ca/news/2013/08/cityfest-cityplace-torontos-newest-festival-saturday|accessdate=May 22, 2018|date=August 14, 2013}}</ref> and LG National Texting Championships 2008\u20132009.<ref>{{cite news|title=LG Creates Game Show Atmosphere for Canadian Texting Championships|url=https://www.bizbash.com/lg_creates_game_show_atmosphere_for_canadian_texting_championships/toronto/story/12373/|accessdate=May 22, 2018|date=August 28, 2008}}</ref> She also worked for brands on their marketing campaigns including [[Virgin Mobile]], [[Axe (brand)|Axe]] and [[Molson Canadian]]'s \"Guy Code Campaign\". Arbour was featured in [[Adweek]] magazine in April 2017 for her work in an advertisement of PMD's Lip Plumping Device.<ref>{{cite news|title=Natural Beauty Is Great. But So Is Natural-ish Beauty, Says This Crazy Ad for a Lip Plumper|url=http://www.adweek.com/creativity/natural-beauty-is-great-but-so-is-natural-ish-beauty-says-this-crazy-ad-for-a-lip-plumper/|accessdate=May 22, 2018|publisher=Adweek|date=April 26, 2017}}</ref>\n\n=== Public speaking ===\nIn 2016 Arbour spoke at the [[TEDxWomen]] event in [[Beverly Hills, California]] as a comedian and social media influencer.<ref>{{cite news|title=\"It\u2019s About Time!\" TEDxWomen Presents TEDxCanonDriveWomen Hits Beverly Hills, CA #itsabouttimetedxwomen|url=http://hipsterwave.com/its-about-time-tedxwomen-presents-tedxcanondrivewomen-hits-beverly-hills-ca-itsabouttimetedxwomen|accessdate=May 22, 2018|date=October 24, 2016|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190124113153/http://hipsterwave.com/its-about-time-tedxwomen-presents-tedxcanondrivewomen-hits-beverly-hills-ca-itsabouttimetedxwomen|archivedate=January 24, 2019}}</ref> She was a speaker at the Archangel Summit 2017 along with [[Daymond John]], [[Simon Sinek]] and [[Danielle LaPorte]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Archangel Summit 2017 \u2013 Superhero Entrepreneurs Who Want To Change The World|url=https://www.meetup.com/Toronto-Entrepreneurs/events/241717509/|accessdate=May 22, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Past Archangel Summit speakers|url=http://www.archangelsummit.com|accessdate=May 22, 2018}}</ref>\n\nAs of April 2018, Arbour has received over 700,000,000 views on her online comedy content. In her first year online she received over 300,000,000 views on her videos and celebrated by hosting the \"World\u2019s Biggest Champagne Shower\" at the Flamingo Hotel Las Vegas.<ref>{{cite news|title=Internet Superstar Nicole Arbour Celebrates 300 Million Views by Hosting Biggest Champagne Shower at GO Pool at Flamingo Las Vegas|url=https://www.vegasnews.com/153311/internet-superstar-nicole-arbour-celebrates-300-million-views-by-hosting-biggest-champagne-shower-at-go-pool-at-flamingo-las-vegas.html|accessdate=May 22, 2018|date=August 28, 2016}}</ref>\n\n== Filmography ==\n=== Film ===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n!Year\n!Title\n!Role\n!Notes\n|-\n|2011\n|''[[Silent But Deadly]]''\n|Jackie\n|\n|-\n|2009\n|''[[You Might as Well Live]]''\n|Regina Manitoba\n|\n|-\n|2008\n|''[[The Rocker (film)|The Rocker]]''\n|Trashy Groupie\n|\n|}\n\n=== Television ===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n!Year\n!Title\n!Role\n!Notes\n|-\n|2014\u20132015\n|''Too Much Information''\n|Herself<ref>{{cite news|title=Too Much Information features cavalcade of comedians|url=https://www.thestar.com/entertainment/television/2014/11/17/too_much_information_features_cavalcade_of_comedians.html|date= November 17, 2014|accessdate=May 16, 2018}}</ref>\n| Series regular\n|-\n|2015\n|''CMT's Hottest''\n|Herself\n|Series regular\n|-\n|2015\n|''CMT's Hottest''\n|Herself\n|Series regular\n|-\n|2009\n|''[[Howie Do It]]''\n|Beautiful Assistant / Spokesmodel\n|Series regular; 7 episodes\n|-\n|2007\n|''[[Winnipeg Comedy Festival]]''\n|Herself\n|Standup Comedian <ref>{{cite web|title=Performers Winnipeg Comedy Festival|url=http://www.winnipegcomedyfestival.com/performers/display,profile/262|accessdate=May 16, 2018}}</ref>\n|-\n|2006-2009\n|''[[Video on Trial]]''\n|Herself\n|Series regular\n|-\n|}\n\n== Awards and recognition ==\n{| class=\"wikitable\" cellpadding=\"6\" style=\"width:85%;\"\n|-\n!Year\n!Award\n!Category\n!Result\n!Ref.\n|-\n| 2017\n| International Pain Foundation Hero of Hope Awards\n| Nerve To Be Heard\n| {{Won}}\n|<ref>{{cite web|title=2017 Hero of Hope Award Winners|url=https://internationalpain.org/heroes-of-hope/|accessdate=May 16, 2018}}</ref>\n|-\n| 2016\n| The Producers Choice Honors\n| Honorary Star on the Hollywood Walk of Fame\n| {{Won}}\n|<ref>{{cite web|title=Celebrity Sightings In Los Angeles|url=https://www.gettyimages.com/event/celebrity-sightings-in-los-angeles-november-09-2016-590323723#/gigi-hadid-is-seen-at-jimmy-kimmel-live-on-november-09-2016-in-los-picture-id622094650|accessdate=May 16, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=2016 The Producers Choice Honors|url=http://producerschoicehonors.com/submissions/alumni/|accessdate=May 16, 2018}}</ref>\n|-\n| 2015\n| [[Shorty Awards]]\n| Best Comedian\n| {{Nom}}\n|<ref>{{cite web|title=Shorty Awards 2015: Nominees Include Shonda Rhimes, Chris Pratt, Laverne Cox (Exclusive)|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/shorty-awards-2015-nominees-include-778517|date=February 3, 2015|publisher=Hollywood Reporter|accessdate=May 16, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Comedian in Social Media - Shorty Awards|url=http://shortyawards.com/category/7th/comedian|accessdate=May 16, 2018}}</ref>\n|-\n| 2009\n| IAB Mixx Awards\n| Branded Content\n| {{Nom}}\n|<ref>{{cite web|title=MIXX Awards Finalists Announced|url=https://www.iab.com/news/mixx-awards-finalists-announced/|accessdate=May 16, 2018}}</ref>\n|-\n|}\n\n== Controversies ==\n=== \"Dear Fat People\" video ===\nIn September 2015, Arbour became the subject of controversy when she posted a [[viral video]] on her YouTube channel titled \"Dear Fat People\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.newsy.com/videos/dear-fat-people-video-sparks-fat-shaming-backlash/|title='Dear Fat People' Video Sparks 'Fat-Shaming' Backlash|last=Rodriguez|first=Karen|date=September 7, 2015|website=Newsy|publisher=|accessdate=September 12, 2015}}</ref> Critics argued that the video endorses [[Anti-fat bias|fat shaming]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cnn.com/2015/09/06/entertainment/fat-shaming-nicole-arbour/|title=Celebrities battle it out over fat-shaming|last=Hetter|first=Katia|date=September 7, 2015|website=[[CNN]]|publisher=|access-date=July 10, 2016}}</ref> The video was temporarily unavailable on [[YouTube]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.medicaldaily.com/pulse/youtube-video-censorship-nicole-arbours-account-gets-suspended-after-shaming-fat-351414|title=YouTube Video Censorship: Nicole Arbour's Account Gets Suspended After Shaming 'Fat People'|last=Castillo|first=Stephanie|date=September 6, 2015|website=[[Medical Daily]]|publisher=|access-date=July 10, 2016}}</ref> over claims that it violated the YouTube terms of service, but was later restored.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.cnn.com/2015/09/06/entertainment/fat-shaming-nicole-arbour/ |title=Fat-shaming: Celebrities battle it out|first= Katia|last= Hetter|work=cnn.com |date= September 8, 2015|accessdate=September 8, 2015}}</ref>\n\nArbour was the subject of both public and celebrity criticism, with model [[Ashley Graham (model)|Ashley Graham]] labelling her comments as \"disgusting\".<ref name=\":1\" /> Director [[Pat Mills (director)|Pat Mills]] fired Arbour from an upcoming movie after seeing the video and was quoted via several sources, \"I'm gay. I was bullied a lot as a kid. I am no stranger to ridicule and loneliness... It's fat-phobic and awful. It went on for over six minutes. I felt like I had been punched in the gut. I was so upset I was shaking like Shelley Duvall in ''[[The Shining (film)|The Shining]]''\".<ref name=\":1\">{{cite web|url=http://www.eonline.com/news/694742/youtube-star-nicole-arbour-fired-from-movie-role-for-cruel-fat-shaming-video|title=YouTube Star Nicole Arbour Fired From Movie Role for ''Cruel Fat-Shaming Video''|last=Harrison|first=Lily|date=September 10, 2015|website=E! Online|publisher=|accessdate=September 11, 2015}}</ref> On September 10, 2015, Arbour, via [[Twitter]] denied ever having any form of involvement in the film.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://m.usmagazine.com/celebrity-news/news/youtube-star-nicole-arbour-fired-from-movie-after-fat-shaming-video-2015119|title=YouTube Star Nicole Arbour Fired From Movie After Fat-Shaming Video - Us Weekly|last=Webber|first=Stephanie|date=September 11, 2015|website=US Weekly|publisher=|access-date=July 10, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.etonline.com/news/171683_nicole_arbour_fired_after_fat_shaming_video_backlash/|title=YouTube Star Nicole Arbour Fired From Film After 'Dear Fat People' Backlash|last=Willis|first=Jackie|date=September 11, 2015|website=ET|publisher=|accessdate=September 27, 2015}}</ref>\n\nSoon after the video, Arbour was fired from her job where she was a choreographer for an anti-bullying video for kids.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.people.com/article/nicole-arbour-fired-movie-job-after-fat-shaming-video|title=Nicole Arbour Responds to Claim She Was Fired from Film Job in Wake of 'Dear Fat People' Backlash|last=Heigl|first=Alex|date=September 11, 2015|website=PEOPLE.com|publisher=|access-date=May 12, 2016}}</ref> The director of the film she was hired to work on said it \"made me never want to see her again\".<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nOn September 16, 2015, Arbour appeared on ''[[The View (U.S. TV series)|The View]]'' to defend her actions in the \"Dear Fat People\" video, stating while on the show \"that video was made to offend people...it's just satire,\" and that the video wasn't supposed to be taken seriously.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.people.com/article/nicole-arbour-refuses-apologize-dear-fat-people-the-view|title=Nicole Arbour Refuses to Apologize for 'Dear Fat People' YouTube Video on The View|last=Olya|first=Gabrielle|date=September 16, 2015|website=PEOPLE.com|publisher=|access-date=|accessdate=September 27, 2015}}</ref> ''[[Time (magazine)|Time]]'' cited an interview stating, \"Arbour doesn't see her comments as bullying, but rather an intense form of truth-telling\".<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=http://time.com/4028119/dear-fat-people-nicole-arbour/|title='Dear Fat People' Comedian Nicole Arbour: 'I'm Not Apologizing'|last=Ross|first=Ashley|date=September 10, 2015|website=TIME.com|publisher=|access-date=July 10, 2016}}</ref> Arbour was quoted in the ''Time'' article, defending her actions: <blockquote>I find seeing someone's head being blown off offensive ... I find children starving in a country with more than enough food offensive. I find women's bodies being mutilated for religious purposes, that is offensive to me. But words and satire I don't find offensive.<ref name=\":2\" /></blockquote>\n\n=== Domestic abuse allegations ===\nOn January 11, 2016, YouTube personality [[Matthew Santoro]] posted \"My Abuse Story\", a video in which he claimed he had been in a physically and emotionally abusive relationship with Arbour, although he did not name her in the video. The video was originally set to private after Santoro ended the relationship but was accidentally made public.<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.dailydot.com/entertainment/matthew-santoro-abusive-relationship/|title=YouTube celebrity Matthew Santoro says ex Nicole Arbour abused him|last=Votta|first=Rae|date=January 12, 2016|website=The Daily Dot|access-date=July 10, 2016}}</ref> Santoro claimed he was manipulated into isolating himself from his friends and family because of Arbour's jealousy, and was later even slapped in the face.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.rawstory.com/2016/01/nicole-arbours-disgusting-response-to-matthew-santoros-allegation-of-abuse/|title=Nicole Arbour's disgusting response to Matthew Santoro's allegation of abuse|last=Kasparian|first=Ana|date=January 14, 2016|website=www.rawstory.com|publisher=|access-date=July 10, 2016}}</ref> Arbour denied the allegations in a YouTube video.<ref name=\":3\" /> Santoro has since removed his original video.\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{IMDb name|2313639}}\n* {{facebook|NicoleArbourfans}}\n* [https://www.youtube.com/user/nicolearbour Nicole Arbour] on [[YouTube]]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Arbour, Nicole}}\n[[Category:1985 births]]\n[[Category:21st-century Canadian actresses]]\n[[Category:21st-century Canadian singers]]\n[[Category:21st-century women singers]]\n[[Category:Actresses from Hamilton, Ontario]]\n[[Category:Canadian YouTubers]]\n[[Category:Canadian cheerleaders]]\n[[Category:Canadian female dancers]]\n[[Category:Canadian female singers]]\n[[Category:Canadian women comedians]]\n[[Category:YouTube controversies]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Musicians from Hamilton, Ontario]]\n[[Category:National Basketball Association cheerleaders]]\n[[Category:Social media influencers]]\n", "name_user": "92.24.131.115", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Nicole_Arbour"}
{"title_page": "Goryeo coinage", "text_new": "{{short description|Currency used in Goryeo}}\n[[File:\ub3d9\uad6d\ud1b5\ubcf4 (\u6771\u570b\u901a\u5bf6) National Museum of Korea.jpg|thumb|right|Two ''Dongguk Tongbo'' (\u6771\u570b\u901a\u5bf6) cash coins.]] \n\n'''Goryeo coinage''' ([[Hanja]]: \u9ad8\u9e97-\u8ca8\u5e63; [[Hangul]]: \uace0\ub824\uc758 \ud654\ud3d0) refers to the different types of coinages of [[Goryeo]].\n\nThe ''\u016dnby\u014fng'' was in circulation for around 300 years and, according to the [[Bank of Korea]], occupies an important place in the history of Korean currency.<ref name=\"\uc624\uacbd\uc12d\">{{cite web |last1=\uc624\uacbd\uc12d |script-title=ko:\ub3c5\ud2b9\ud55c \ud615\ud0dc\ub97c \uc9c0\ub2cc \uc740\ubcd1(\u9280\u7501)\ud654\ud3d0 |url=https://www.bok.or.kr/portal/bbs/P0000547/view.do?nttId=17770&menuNo=200387 |website=[[Bank of Korea]] |accessdate=3 October 2019 |language=ko}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"\uae40\ub3d9\ucca0\">{{cite web |last1=\uae40\ub3d9\ucca0 |script-title=ko:3) \ud654\ud3d0 \ubc0f \ucc28\ub300\ubc95 |url=http://contents.history.go.kr/front/nh/view.do?levelId=nh_014_0040_0020_0030 |website=History Net |publisher=[[National Institute of Korean History]] |accessdate=29 December 2019 |language=ko}}</ref>\n\n== History ==\n{{See also|Korean mun#History}}\n\n=== Early period ===\nThe main currencies used in Goryeo after its founding were [[Ancient Chinese coinage|Chinese money]], such as [[Tang dynasty|Tang]] and [[Song dynasty|Song]] dynasty coins, and [[commodity money]], such as cloth ({{Korean|\ud3ec\ud654|\u5e03\u8ca8|labels=no}}).<ref name=\"\uc6d0\uc720\ud55c\">{{cite web |last1=\uc6d0\uc720\ud55c |script-title=ko:\ucca0\uc804(\u9435\u9322) |url=http://encykorea.aks.ac.kr/Contents/Item/E0056169 |website=Encyclopedia of Korean Culture |publisher=Academy of Korean Studies |accessdate=13 October 2019 |language=ko}}</ref> Goryeo did not have a unified legal currency, and each region, ruled by the quasi-independent ''hojok'' ({{Korean|\ud638\uc871|\u8c6a\u65cf|labels=no}}) regional lords,{{sfn|Kim|2012|p=122}} used a different currency.<ref name=\"\uc6d0\uc720\ud55c\" />\n\nFollowing the [[Khitan people|Khitan]] destruction of the kingdom of [[Balhae]], which Goryeo had considered a country of kinship, [[Taejo of Goryeo]] proclaimed a ban on the circulation of all coins in 942.{{sfn|Jun|2014|pp=261\u2013262}} This was to sanction trade with the hated Khitans, who used metallic money, and protect Goryeo's metal reserves.{{sfn|Jun|2014|pp=261\u2013262}}{{sfn|Jun|2014|p=276}} In addition, Goryeo prepared itself for a conflict with the Khitan Empire.{{sfn|Kim|2012|pp=141\u2013142}}{{sfn|Lee|1984|p=125}} Taejo's prohibition in 942 indicates that, to some degree, coins had been circulating in Goryeo.{{sfn|Jun|2014|p=269}} Following the prohibition, rice and cloth were the [[medium of exchange]].{{sfn|Jun|2014|p=262}} Likewise, cloth was the medium of exchange for everyday transactions in the [[Liao dynasty]] and [[Jin dynasty (1115\u20131234)|Jin dynasty]].{{sfn|Jun|2014|p=268}} During this period in Goryeo, agriculture achieved high productivity and living standards improved; rice and textile production enabled Goryeo to increase its military strength.{{sfn|Jun|2014|p=262}} The ban on coins lasted until 996,{{sfn|Jun|2014|p=262}} three years after Goryeo had resumed diplomatic relations with the Liao dynasty.{{sfn|Jun|2014|p=270}}\n\nIn 996, [[Seongjong of Goryeo]] minted iron coins to trade with the Khitans, who used iron coins.{{sfn|Jun|2014|pp=270\u2013271}} The coins may have been issued to promote centralization.<ref name=\"\uc6d0\uc720\ud55c\" /> As far as can be established, the iron coins were not inscribed.{{sfn|Jun|2014|p=271}} The government made many efforts to promote the use of coins instead of commodity money;<ref name=\"History Net\">{{cite web |script-title=ko:\ud654\ud3d0\uc758 \uc0ac\uc6a9 |url=http://contents.history.go.kr/front/hm/view.do?treeId=010402&tabId=03&levelId=hm_059_0040 |website=History Net |publisher=National Institute of Korean History |accessdate=4 November 2019 |language=ko}}</ref> in 997, [[Mokjong of Goryeo]] prohibited the monetary use of hemp cloth,<ref name=\"Lee\">{{cite web |last1=Lee |first1=Hun-Chang |script-title=ko:\uace0\ub824\uc2dc\ub300 \uc740\ud654\u00b7\uc9c0\ud3d0\uc758 \uc81c\ud55c\uc801 \uc720\ud1b5 |url=http://contents.history.go.kr/front/km/view.do?levelId=km_008_0030_0010_0040 |website=History Net |publisher=National Institute of Korean History |accessdate=4 November 2019 |language=ko}}</ref> which, at the time, was the most widely used currency for everyday transactions.<ref name=\"History Net\" /> However, due to opposition, including from the nobility,<ref name=\"\uc6d0\uc720\ud55c\" /> the government repealed the prohibition and shifted its policy in 1002: the distribution of the coins was stopped and the public was allowed to use any currency.<ref name=\"Lee\" /><ref name=\"\uae40\uc7ac\uba85\">{{cite web |last1=\uae40\uc7ac\uba85 |script-title=ko:\uac74\uc6d0\uc911\ubcf4(\u4e7e\u5143\u91cd\u5bf6) |url=http://encykorea.aks.ac.kr/Contents/Index?contents_id=E0002015 |website=Encyclopedia of Korean Culture |publisher=Academy of Korean Studies |accessdate=15 October 2019 |language=ko}}</ref> Meanwhile, coins continued to be used at tea and wine shops (\u8336\u9152\u5e97) and restaurants.<ref name=\"\uc6d0\uc720\ud55c\" /><ref name=\"Lee\" /><ref name=\"\uae40\uc7ac\uba85\" />\n\nThe \"''Geonwon Jungbo''\", an iron coin inscribed with ''Geonwon Jungbo'' ({{Korean|\uac74\uc6d0\uc911\ubcf4|\u4e7e\u5143\u91cd\u5bf6|labels=no}}) on one side and ''Dongguk'' ({{Korean|\ub3d9\uad6d|\u6771\u570b|labels=no}}) on the other side, was excavated from a Goryeo tomb in the vicinity of [[Kaesong]], the capital of Goryeo, in the early 1910s; it was unearthed along with bronze ''Geonwon Jungbo'', ''Dongguk Tongbo'', and ''Dongguk Jungbo'' coins.<ref name=\"\uae40\uc7ac\uba85\" /><ref name=\"\uac74\uc6d0\uc911\ubcf4\">{{cite web |script-title=ko:\uac74\uc6d0\uc911\ubcf4 |url=http://contents.history.go.kr/front/ti/view.do?treeId=04013&levelId=ti_013_0150 |website=History Net |publisher=National Institute of Korean History |accessdate=15 October 2019 |language=ko}}</ref> However, its relation to Goryeo's iron coins minted in 996 is controversial.{{sfn|Boling|1988|p=1}} Gary Ashkenazy of \"Primal Trek\" says that the ''Geonwon Jungbo'' is not mentioned in Korean historical sources and was not cataloged until 1938 in the {{Nihongo| |\u6771\u4e9e\u9322\u5fd7|T\u014da senshi}} by Masahiro Okudaira, in which it is attributed to Goryeo.<ref name=\"Ashkenazy\">{{cite web |last1=Ashkenazy |first1=Gary |title=Korean Coins |url=http://primaltrek.com/koreancoins.html |website=Primal Trek |accessdate=16 October 2019 |language=en}}</ref>\n\nIn Korea, the ''Geonwon Jungbo'' is considered a Goryeo coin.<ref name=\"\uc6d0\uc720\ud55c\" /><ref name=\"\uae40\uc7ac\uba85\" /><ref name=\"\uac74\uc6d0\uc911\ubcf4\" /> The original coin, called the ''Qianyuan zhongbao'' in Chinese, dates to 759 during the Tang dynasty; the ''Geonwon Jungbo'', in contrast, is inscribed with ''Dongguk'' on the [[Obverse and reverse|reverse]].{{sfn|Jun|2014|p=271}} ''Dongguk'' was one of Goryeo's many names, along with ''Samhan'', ''Haedong'', ''Dongbang'', and ''Cheonggu''.{{sfn|Breuker|2010|pp=36\u201337}} According to Jun Seong Ho of the [[Academy of Korean Studies]]: \"Since cast coins cannot be altered, the coin cannot have been recast preserving the Tang inscription. Most probably, the coin was a heavy denomination cast by the [Goryeo] mint in the late tenth century.\"{{sfn|Jun|2014|p=271}} Furthermore, Goryeo and Tang coins have a different metal composition.{{sfn|Jun|2014|p=271}}\n\nIn China, the ''Geonwon Jungbo'' is viewed as a Goryeo coin or a Balhae coin.<ref name=\"\u738b\u7956\u8fdc\">{{cite web |last1=\u738b\u7956\u8fdc |script-title=zh:\u4e7e\u5143\u91cd\u5b9d\u80cc\u4e1c\u56fd |url=http://www.cssn.cn/sjs/sjs_hqzs/201709/t20170919_3644954.shtml |website=Chinese Social Sciences Net |accessdate=15 October 2019 |language=zh |date=19 September 2017}}</ref> The \"Goryeo coin\" viewpoint is represented by the ''T\u014da senshi'', published in 1938.<ref name=\"\u738b\u7956\u8fdc\" /> Wang Zuyuan, a proponent of the more recent \"Balhae coin\" viewpoint, says that Balhae always had close relations with and was strongly supported politically, economically, culturally, and militarily by the Tang dynasty; therefore, he concludes that Balhae, also known as \"''Haidong Shengguo''\" (\u6d77\u6771\u76db\u570b), minted the ''Geonwon Jungbo'' to show its loyalty to the Tang dynasty during the reign of [[Emperor Suzong of Tang|Emperor Suzong]] ({{reign|756|762}}).<ref name=\"\u738b\u7956\u8fdc\" /> However, Balhae coins have not been excavated.{{sfn|Kim|2008|p=304}}<ref>{{cite web |last1=\u9676\u77ed\u623f |script-title=zh:\u53e4\u6e24\u6d77\u56fd\u662f\u5426\u53d1\u884c\u94f8\u5e01?\u51fa\u571f\u5f00\u6cf0\u5143\u5b9d\u6216\u4e3a\u8236\u6765\u54c1 |url=http://www.chinanews.com/cul/2014/10-07/6651652.shtml |website=chinanews.com |publisher=\u5e7f\u5dde\u65e5\u62a5 |accessdate=22 October 2019 |language=zh}}</ref> Alexander Alexeyvich Kim says, \"One of the arguments the Chinese frequently use when they describe [Balhae] as 'provincial power of the Tang Empire' is the absence of [Balhae] coins.\"{{sfn|Kim|2008|p=304}} Russian archaeologists argue that Balhae may have used foreign currency, as many independent and developed states did.{{sfn|Kim|2008|p=304}}\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Inscription !! [[Hangul]] !! [[McCune\u2013Reischauer]] !! [[Revised Romanisation]] !! Image \n|- \n| \u4e7e\u5143\u91cd\u5bf6{{efn|In the modern era these cash coins are mostly unearthed in the Chinese province of [[Liaoning]] and [[North Korea]]. Some of them being unearthed in the city of [[Kaiyuan, Liaoning]].<ref name=\"BaiduNumismatics2011\">{{cite web|url= https://wk.baidu.com/view/254c43c5f705cc17552709d2?pcf=2|title= 2011\u5e74\u4e2d\u56fd\u94b1\u5e01\u5b66\u7814\u7a76\u7efc\u8ff0_\u56fe\u6587_\u767e\u5ea6\u6587\u5e93.|date=22 January 2014|accessdate=4 October 2019|work= A Summary of the Research on Chinese Numismatic Studies in 2011 (2011\u5e74\u4e2d\u56fd\u94b1\u5e01\u5b66\u7814\u7a76\u7efc\u8ff0)|publisher= [[Baidu]]|language=zh-cn}}</ref> The iron cash coins are more commonly found than the bronze ones. Currently only 10 pieces of the ''Geonwon Jungbo'' are known to exist making it an extremely valued object among [[East Asia]]n coin collectors.<ref name=\"SOUC201205021\">{{cite web|url= http://mall.cnki.net/magazine/article/SOUC201205021.htm|title= \"\u4e7e\u5143\u91cd\u5b9d\u00b7\u4e1c\u56fd\"\u94b1\u662f\u9ad8\u4e3d\u94b1\u5417?.|date=2 May 2012|accessdate=4 October 2019|work= mall.cnki.net/magazine/|language=zh-cn}}</ref>}}<br>\u6771\u570b || \uac74\uc6d0\uc911\ubcf4<br>\ub3d9\uad6d || ''K\u014fnw\u014fn Chungbo''<br>''Tongguk'' || ''Geonwon Jungbo''<br>''Dongguk'' || \n|}\n\n=== Middle period ===\nGoryeo issued new currencies during the reign of [[Sukjong of Goryeo]] ({{reign|1095|1105}}) based on proposals by the Buddhist monk [[Uichon]] and the military officer [[Yun Gwan]].<ref name=\"\ud45c\uc815\ud6c8\">{{cite web |last1=\ud45c\uc815\ud6c8 |script-title=ko:\uc758\ucc9c |url=https://terms.naver.com/entry.nhn?cid=59015&docId=3572347&categoryId=59015 |website=Naver Encyclopedia of Knowledge |accessdate=14 November 2019 |language=ko}}</ref> Uichon, who was a younger brother of Sukjong, argued for the implementation of a monetary economy, having experienced its convenience and efficiency in the [[Song dynasty]].<ref name=\"\ud45c\uc815\ud6c8\" /> Moreover, his proposed reform was intended to centralize the commerce and economy, which were dominated by the nobility.<ref name=\"\ud45c\uc815\ud6c8\" /> Uichon established a mint bureau in 1097;{{sfn|Jun|2014|p=270}} coins, named after [[Names of Korea#Sobriquets of Korea|sobriquets of Goryeo]], such as the ''Dongguk Tongbo'', ''Samhan Tongbo'', and ''Haedong Tongbo'' were subsequently minted and circulated. Beginning in 1101, a uniquely shaped silver currency called the ''\u016dnby\u014fng'' ({{Korean|\uc740\ubcd1|\u9280\u7501|labels=no}}), meaning \"silver vase\" in [[Korean language|Korean]], was cast and circulated.<ref name=\"\ubbfc\ubcd1\ud558\">{{cite web |last1=\ubbfc\ubcd1\ud558 |script-title=ko:\uc740\ubcd1(\u9280\u7501) |url=http://encykorea.aks.ac.kr/Contents/Item/E0042821 |website=Encyclopedia of Korean Culture |publisher=Academy of Korean Studies |accessdate=28 November 2019 |language=ko}}</ref>\n\nGoryeo bronze coins resembled standard East Asian coins of the time, but differed in that they were inscribed with a national name instead of an [[Regnal year|era name]].{{sfn|Jun|2014|pp=271\u2013272}} Sukjong actively promoted the use of coins.<ref name=\"History Net\" /> After a five-year delay due to opposition,<ref name=\"\uae40\ub3d9\ucca0\" /> 15,000 ''[[String of cash coins (currency unit)|gwan]]'' (or 15 million pieces) of the ''Haedong Tongbo'' were minted in 1102.<ref name=\"Lee\" />{{sfn|Boling|1988|p=1}}<ref name=\"\ubbfc\ubcd1\ud558\" /> Goryeo had circulated coins in the past, but this was the first full-scale circulation.<ref name=\"\ud45c\uc815\ud6c8\" /> The ''Sikhwaji'' ({{Korean|\uc2dd\ud654\uc9c0|\u98df\u8ca8\u5fd7|labels=no|lit=''Treatise on Food and Money''}}) in the ''[[History of Goryeo]]'' says: \"There is nothing more important than coinage, which may benefit our country and enrich the people ... It is only now that we have issued decrees about the minting of metal coinage.\"<ref name=\"History Net 2\">{{cite web |title=Korean Currency |url=http://contents.history.go.kr/front/eng/tz/view.do?levelId=tz_b25 |website=History Net |publisher=National Institute of Korean History |accessdate=7 December 2019 |language=en}}</ref> To promote their use, the newly minted coins were distributed to government officials and soldiers, and new shops were installed in the capital; in 1104, the states and prefectures were ordered to open new wine shops and restaurants.<ref name=\"Lee\" /> Sukjong died in 1105. In the following year, his monetary policy was met with stiff resistance from officials in both the central and provincial governments.<ref name=\"Lee\" /> Despite the opposition, [[Yejong of Goryeo]] doubled down on Sukjong's monetary policy in 1112.<ref name=\"Lee\" /> However, coins ultimately failed to gain widespread use in Goryeo.<ref name=\"Lee\" /><ref name=\"History Net 2\" /> Silver currency, on the other hand, was used continuously until the end of the dynasty.<ref name=\"Lee\" /> Xu Jing, a Song dynasty envoy who visited Goryeo in 1123, observed the use of the ''\u016dnby\u014fng'', but not coins, as a currency.<ref name=\"Lee\" />\n\nThe ''\u016dnby\u014fng'' \"silver vase\", popularly called the ''hwalgu'' ({{Korean|\ud65c\uad6c|\u95ca\u53e3|labels=no}}) for its broad mouth,{{sfn|Ledyard|1995|p=295}} was imprinted with a government seal and first issued in 1101.<ref name=\"Lee\" />{{sfn|Jun|2014|p=273}} It was made with one ''[[Korean units of measurement#Weight|geun]]'' ({{Korean|\uadfc|\u65a4|labels=no}}) of silver and designed to resemble the [[Cartography|cartographic]] outline of the Korean Peninsula.<ref name=\"\ubbfc\ubcd1\ud558\" />{{sfn|Ledyard|1995|p=240}} The ''\u016dnby\u014fng'' was made because of the illegal manufacture of silver currency;<ref name=\"Lee\" /> all other silver currencies were prohibited by the government.{{sfn|Jun|2014|p=273}} As a stable, standardized currency, the ''\u016dnby\u014fng'' was used throughout the kingdom in both public finance and private trade; it was also used to pay taxes.{{sfn|Jun|2014|p=273}} The ''\u016dnby\u014fng'' was widely used as a currency by the nobility, whereas grain and cloth were used by the common people.{{sfn|Kim|2012|p=138}} Furthermore, the ''\u016dnby\u014fng'' was used mainly in large transactions.<ref name=\"Lee\" />{{sfn|Ledyard|1995|p=240}} According to Jun Seong Ho: \"For roughly 150 years from the early twelfth to the mid thirteenth century, silver was the main currency of [Goryeo].\"{{sfn|Jun|2014|p=273}} Silver had been used as a currency before the ''\u016dnby\u014fng'' was made.<ref name=\"Lee\" /> Korean silver metallurgy was advanced, and Koreans exported silver, possibly in the form of [[ingot]]s, to the Jurchens in the mid 10th century;{{sfn|Jun|2014|p=269}} Korean silver metallurgy was exported to the Jurchens in 1102.{{sfn|Jun|2014|p=273}} The ''\u016dnby\u014fng'' remained the only standardized silver currency in [[East Asia]] until the 16th century with the start of a silver mining boom in Japan,{{sfn|Jun|2014|p=275}} enabled by the introduction of [[cupellation]] from Korea in 1533.<ref>{{cite web |title=Refining Silver: \"Haifuki Cupellation Method\" |url=https://ginzan.city.ohda.lg.jp/wh/en/technology/haifuki.html |website=Iwami Ginzan World Heritage Center |publisher=Shimane Prefectural Government |accessdate=29 December 2019 |language=en}}</ref>{{sfn|Carlson|2012|p=157}}\n\nGoryeo was a period of flourishing commerce, and Goryeo actively engaged in commercial activity with the Song dynasty during the 11th and 12th centuries.{{sfn|Lee|2017|p=52}} Song dynasty coins circulated in many parts of Asia.<ref name=\"\uae40\ub3d9\ucca0\" /> Goryeo, too, imported coins from the Song dynasty; more Song dynasty coins have been excavated than Goryeo coins in Korea.<ref name=\"Lee\" /> However, they were not necessarily used as a currency, but rather as a [[Offering (Buddhism)|religious offering]] or [[grave good]].<ref name=\"Lee\" /> In 1199, the Song government prohibited the export of coins to Goryeo and Japan.<ref name=\"\uae40\ub3d9\ucca0\" /><ref name=\"Lee\" />\n\n=== Late period ===\nGoryeo experienced a silver famine in the 13th century due to [[Mongol invasions of Goryeo|Mongol invasions]].{{sfn|Jun|2014|p=274}}{{sfn|Lee|2017|p=64}} By the late 13th century, Goryeo was depleted of most of its silver by the [[Yuan dynasty]].{{sfn|Jun|2014|p=274}} Beginning with the reign of [[Chungnyeol of Goryeo]], the Yuan dynasty assumed control of Goryeo's monetary system and imposed its paper money; thus, Goryeo lost its monetary sovereignty.{{sfn|Jun|2014|pp=274\u2013275}} The destabilizing introduction of a new currency demonetized the economy.{{sfn|Jun|2014|p=276}}\n\nThe shortage of silver in Goryeo led to the [[debasement]] and [[Counterfeit money|counterfeiting]] of silver currency; the Goryeo government experienced problems with the ''\u016dnby\u014fng''.<ref name=\"Lee\" /> Goryeo's \"Bureau of Capital City Markets\" ({{Korean|\uacbd\uc2dc\uc11c|\u4eac\u5e02\u7f72|labels=no}}) adjusted the value of the ''\u016dnby\u014fng'' annually according to the harvest; in 1282, the value of one ''\u016dnby\u014fng'' was set at 15 to 16 ''[[Korean units of measurement#Volume|seok]]'' ({{Korean|\uc11d|\u77f3|labels=no}}) of rice in the capital and 18 to 19 ''seok'' of rice in the provinces.<ref name=\"Lee\" /><ref name=\"Bank of Korea\">{{cite web |last1=\uc624\uacbd\uc12d |script-title=ko:\ub3c5\ud2b9\ud55c \ud615\ud0dc\ub97c \uc9c0\ub2cc \uc740\ubcd1(\u9280\u7501)\ud654\ud3d0 |url=https://www.bok.or.kr/portal/bbs/P0000547/view.do?nttId=17770&menuNo=200387 |website=[[Bank of Korea]] |accessdate=3 October 2019 |language=ko}}</ref> The high value of the ''\u016dnby\u014fng'' led to the use of silver [[ingot]]s called \"''swae\u016dn''\" ({{Korean|\uc1c4\uc740|\u788e\u9280|labels=no|lit=broken silver}}) as a currency, which were valued based on weight.<ref name=\"Lee\" /> However, they were prohibited in 1287 because of the appearance of counterfeits mixed with copper.<ref name=\"Lee\" /><ref name=\"\uace0\ub824\uc0ac\">{{cite web |title=\uc740\uacfc \ub3d9\uc744 \uc11e\uc5b4 \uc8fc\uc870\ud558\ub294 \uc77c\uc744 \uae08\uc9c0\ud558\ub2e4 |url=http://db.history.go.kr/KOREA/item/level.do?itemId=kr&bookId=%E5%BF%97&types=r#detail/kr_079r_0010_0030_0100 |website=Korean History Database |publisher=National Institute of Korean History |accessdate=15 February 2020 |language=ko}}</ref> The ''\u016dnby\u014fng'' was also counterfeited, and had been since its inception; as the ''\u016dnby\u014fng'' became increasingly debased with copper,{{efn|The ''\u016dnby\u014fng'' was originally composed of 80% silver and 20% copper.{{sfn|Jun|2014|p=273}}}} its value decreased, and by 1328 the value of one ''\u016dnby\u014fng'' of the highest quality dropped to 10 bolts of cloth.<ref name=\"Lee\" /> In 1331, the Goryeo government abolished the ''\u016dnby\u014fng'' and replaced it with the miniaturized \"''so \u016dnby\u014fng''\" ({{Korean|\uc18c\uc740\ubcd1|\u5c0f\u9280\u7501|labels=no|lit=small ''\u016dnby\u014fng''}}), which was valued at 15 bolts of cloth.{{sfn|Jun|2014|pp=275\u2013276}}\n\nYuan paper money was introduced to Goryeo in 1270.<ref name=\"Lee\" /> In 1287, the Yuan dynasty decreed the use of the ''Zhiyuan baochao'' ({{Korean|\uc9c0\uc6d0\ubcf4\ucd08|\u81f3\u5143\u5bf6\u9214|labels=no}}) and ''Zhongtong baochao'' ({{Korean|\uc911\ud1b5\ubcf4\ucd08|\u4e2d\u7d71\u5bf6\u9214|labels=no}}) in Goryeo.<ref name=\"Lee\" /><ref name=\"\uace0\ub824\uc0ac\" /> Approximately 100,000 ''jeong'' ({{Korean|\uc815|\u9320|labels=no}}) of ''baochao'' were circulated in Goryeo.<ref name=\"Lee\" /> The ''baochao'' was used extensively in trade with the Yuan dynasty.<ref name=\"Lee\" /> During its [[Mongol invasions of Japan|invasions of Japan]], the Yuan dynasty paid for ships and soldiers in Goryeo with ''baochao'' paper money.<ref name=\"Lee\" /> According to Hun-Chang Lee of [[Korea University]]'s Department of Economics, the inflow of paper currency and outflow of silver currency harmed the development of currency in Korea.<ref name=\"Lee\" /> Meanwhile, the Yuan dynasty exported large quantities of coin to Japan, which had not minted its own coins since the late 10th century.<ref name=\"Lee\" />{{sfn|Jun|2014|p=274}} In the ''Sinan'' shipwreck of 1323, approximately 28 tons of coin were being transported by ship from China to Japan before sinking off the coast of the Korean Peninsula.{{sfn|von Glahn|2014|p=272}}\n\nYuan paper money was abolished in 1356 with Goryeo's independence from the Yuan dynasty.<ref name=\"Lee\" /> Instead, silver currency and hemp cloth stamped with a government seal were used as currencies.<ref name=\"Lee\" /> During the end of the Goryeo period, the monetary system was in a state of disarray, and various currencies were debased.<ref name=\"\uad8c\uc778\ud601\">{{cite web |last1=\uad8c\uc778\ud601 |script-title=ko:\uc800\ud654(\u696e\u8ca8) |url=https://encykorea.aks.ac.kr/Contents/Item/E0049125 |website=Encyclopedia of Korean Culture |publisher=Academy of Korean Studies |accessdate=1 April 2020 |language=ko}}</ref> Thus, in 1391, the Korean government introduced a new monetary system, consisting of both metallic currency ({{Korean|\uc804\ud654|\u9322\u8ca8|Jeonhwa|labels=no}}) and paper currency ({{Korean|\uc800\ud654|\u696e\u8ca8|Jeohwa|labels=no}}).<ref name=\"\uad8c\uc778\ud601\" /> The Goryeo dynasty transitioned into the [[Joseon|Joseon dynasty]] in 1392. ''Jeohwa'' paper money continued to be used during the early Joseon period.<ref name=\"\uad8c\uc778\ud601\" /> Meanwhile, the ''\u016dnby\u014fng'' finally came to an end in 1408 after 300 years.<ref name=\"\uc624\uacbd\uc12d\" /> A specimen of the miniaturized \"''so \u016dnby\u014fng''\", presumably dating to the late Goryeo period, has been discovered and currently resides in the [[Bank of Korea Money Museum]], but a specimen of the larger original ''\u016dnby\u014fng'' has yet to be found.<ref name=\"\uc624\uacbd\uc12d\" />\n\n== List of Goryeo cash coins by inscription ==\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Inscription !! [[Hangul]] !! [[McCune\u2013Reischauer]] !! [[Revised Romanisation]] !! [[Chinese script styles|Scripts]] !! Date of casting !! Diameter<br>(in millimeter) !! Weight<br>(in grams) !! Image\n|- \n| \u6771\u570b\u901a\u5bf6 || \ub3d9\uad6d\ud1b5\ubcf4 || Dong kuk T'ong Bo || Dong Guk Tong Bo || [[Seal script]] (\u7bc6\u66f8), [[Clerical script]] (\u96b8\u66f8), [[Regular script]] (\u6977\u66f8), and [[Semi-cursive script|Running script]] (\u884c\u66f8) || 998\u20131097 AD || 23 ~ 25 || 2.4 ~ 3 || [[File:\ub3d9\uad6d\ud1b5\ubcf4 (\u6771\u570b\u901a\u5bf6) National Museum of Korea.jpg|75px]]\n|-\n| \u6771\u570b\u91cd\u5bf6 || \ub3d9\uad6d\uc911\ubcf4 || Dong Kuk Chung Bo || Dong Guk Jung Bo || Regular script (\u6977\u66f8) || 998\u20131097 AD || 24 ~ 25 || 2.8 ~ 3.6{{efn|Specimens weighing as much 4.2 grams have been recorded.}} || [[File:\u6771\u56fd\u91cd\u5bf3 - Dr. Luke Roberts 01.jpg|75px]]\n|-\n| \u4e09\u97d3\u901a\u5bf6 || \uc0bc\ud55c\ud1b5\ubcf4 || Sam Han T'ong Bo || Sam Han Tong Bo || Seal script (\u7bc6 \u66f8), Clerical script (\u96b8\u66f8) and Running script (\u884c\u66f8) || 1097\u20131105 AD || 23 ~ 25 || 2.6 ~ 3.4{{efn|Specimens weighing as little 2.1 grams have been recorded.}} || [[File:Leon de Rosny-Les Coreens-Apercu-ethnographique-et-historique-fig3.png|75px]]\n|-\n| \u53c1\u97d3\u901a\u5bf6{{efn|An extremely rare variant of the ''Samhan Tongbo'' ({{lang|ko-Hang|\uc0bc\ud55c\ud1b5\ubcf4}}, \u4e09\u97d3\u901a\u5bf6) cash coin exists that bears the character {{linktext|\u53c1}} written in \"official script\" instead of {{linktext|\u4e09}}, of which only 2 have currently been found.<ref name=\"Ashkenazy\" />}} || \uc0bc\ud55c\ud1b5\ubcf4 || Sam Han T'ong Bo || Sam Han Tong Bo || \"Official Script\" || 1097\u20131105 AD || || || \n|-\n| \u4e09\u97d3\u91cd\u5bf6 || \uc0bc\ud55c\uc911\ubcf4 || Sam Han Chung Bo || Sam Han Jung Bo || Regular script (\u6977\u66f8) || 1097\u20131105 AD || 25 || 4 || [[File:\u4e09\u97d3\u91cd\u5bf3 - Dr. Luke Roberts 01.jpg|75px]]\n|-\n| \u6d77\u6771\u901a\u5bf6 || \ud574\ub3d9\ud1b5\ubcf4 || Hae Dong T'ong Bo || Hae Dong Tong Bo || Seal script (\u7bc6\u66f8), Clerical script (\u96b8\u66f8), Regular script (\u6977\u66f8), and Running script (\u884c\u66f8) || 1097\u20131105 AD || 25 || 2.9 || [[File:\u6d77\u6771\u901a\u5bf3 - Dr. Luke Roberts 01.jpg|75px]]\n|-\n| \u6d77\u6771\u91cd\u5bf6 || \ud574\ub3d9\uc911\ubcf4 || Hae Dong Chung Bo || Hae Dong Jung Bo || Regular script (\u6977\u66f8) || 1097\u20131105 AD || 25 || 3.1 ~ 4 || \n|-\n| \u6d77\u6771\u5143\u5bf6{{efn|These cash coins are extremely rare and the only recent specimens of the ''Haedong Wonbo'' (\u6d77\u6771\u5143\u5bf6) that have been excavated were found in an area near [[Kaesong]], [[North Korea]].}} || \ud574\ub3d9\uc6d0\ubcf4 || Hae Dong W\u014fn Bo || Hae Dong Won Bo || Regular script (\u6977\u66f8) || 1097\u20131105 AD || || || \n|}\n\n== Notes ==\n{{Notelist}}\n\n== References ==\n\n=== Citations ===\n{{Reflist}}\n\n=== Sources ===\n* {{citation |last=Boling |first=Joseph E. |date=July 1988 |title=Beyond Cash - A Numismatic Survey of Korea |url=http://www.moneta-coins.com/library/Korea%20-%20A%20Numismatic%20Survey%20-%20Boling.pdf |magazine=Coin World |language=en}}\n* {{citation |last1=Breuker |first1=Remco E. |title=Establishing a Pluralist Society in Medieval Korea, 918-1170: History, Ideology and Identity in the Kory\u014f Dynasty |date=2010 |publisher=BRILL |isbn=9789004183254 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=wZx0VvujPqcC |language=en}}\n* {{citation |last1=Carlson |first1=Jon D. |title=Myths, State Expansion, and the Birth of Globalization: A Comparative Perspective |date=January 2012 |publisher=Palgrave Macmillan |isbn=978-1-137-01045-2 |edition=1st |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=uebJAAAAQBAJ |language=en}}\n* {{citation |last1=Jun |first1=Seong Ho |title=Monetary authority independence and stability in medieval Korea: the Kory\u014f monetary system through four centuries of East Asian transformations, 918-1392 |journal=[[Financial History Review]] |date=22 December 2014 |volume=21 |issue=3 |pages=259\u2013280 |doi=10.1017/S0968565014000213 |publisher=[[Cambridge University Press]] |language=en}}\n* {{citation |last1=Kim |first1=Alexander Alexeyvich |title=Archeological Studies of Bohai in Russia |journal=Oriens Extremus |date=2008 |volume=47 |pages=302\u2013312 |language=en |issn=0030-5197 |jstor=24048057}}\n* {{citation |last1=Kim |first1=Jinwung |title=A History of Korea: From \"Land of the Morning Calm\" to States in Conflict |date=2012 |publisher=Indiana University Press |isbn=9780253000248 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=s2EVi-MpnUsC |language=en}}\n* {{citation |last1=Ledyard |first1=Gari |editor1-last=Harley |editor1-first=J. B. |editor2-last=Woodward |editor2-first=David |title=The History of Cartography, Volume 2, Book 2 |date=February 1995 |publisher=University of Chicago Press |isbn=9780226316376 |url=https://www.press.uchicago.edu/ucp/books/book/chicago/H/bo3617125.html |language=en |chapter=Chapter 10: Cartography in Korea}}\n* {{citation |last1=Lee |first1=Kang Hahn |title=Kory\u014f's Trade with the Outer World |journal=Korean Studies |date=2017 |volume=41 |issue=1 |pages=52\u201374 |doi=10.1353/ks.2017.0018 |publisher=University of Hawai'i Press |language=en}}\n* {{citation |last1=Lee |first1=Ki-Baik |title=A New History of Korea |date=1984 |publisher=Harvard University Press |isbn=9780674615762 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=g2mdVwXpMzwC |language=en}}\n* {{citation |last1=von Glahn |first1=Richard |title=The Ningbo-Hakata Merchant Network and the Reorientation of East Asian Maritime Trade, 1150\u20131350 |journal=Harvard Journal of Asiatic Studies |date=2014 |volume=74 |issue=2 |pages=249\u2013279 |doi=10.1353/jas.2014.0029 |language=en}}\n\n{{Commonscat|Coins of Goryeo}} \n\n{{Historical currencies of Korea}} \n{{Goryeo topics}} \n{{Korean cash coin}} \n\n[[Category:Medieval currencies]]\n[[Category:Currencies of Korea]] \n[[Category:Cash coins]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Currency used in Goryeo}}\n[[File:\ub3d9\uad6d\ud1b5\ubcf4 (\u6771\u570b\u901a\u5bf6) National Museum of Korea.jpg|thumb|right|Two ''Dongguk Tongbo'' (\u6771\u570b\u901a\u5bf6) cash coins.]] \n\n'''Goryeo coinage''' ([[Hanja]]: \u9ad8\u9e97-\u8ca8\u5e63; [[Hangul]]: \uace0\ub824\uc758 \ud654\ud3d0) refers to the different types of coinages of [[Goryeo]].\n\nThe ''\u016dnby\u014fng'' was in circulation for around 300 years and, according to the [[Bank of Korea]], occupies an important place in the history of Korean currency.<ref name=\"\uc624\uacbd\uc12d\">{{cite web |last1=\uc624\uacbd\uc12d |script-title=ko:\ub3c5\ud2b9\ud55c \ud615\ud0dc\ub97c \uc9c0\ub2cc \uc740\ubcd1(\u9280\u7501)\ud654\ud3d0 |url=https://www.bok.or.kr/portal/bbs/P0000547/view.do?nttId=17770&menuNo=200387 |website=[[Bank of Korea]] |accessdate=3 October 2019 |language=ko}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"\uae40\ub3d9\ucca0\">{{cite web |last1=\uae40\ub3d9\ucca0 |script-title=ko:3) \ud654\ud3d0 \ubc0f \ucc28\ub300\ubc95 |url=http://contents.history.go.kr/front/nh/view.do?levelId=nh_014_0040_0020_0030 |website=History Net |publisher=[[National Institute of Korean History]] |accessdate=29 December 2019 |language=ko}}</ref>\n\n== History ==\n{{See also|Korean mun#History}}\n\n=== Early period ===\nThe main currencies used in Goryeo after its founding were [[Ancient Chinese coinage|Chinese money]], such as [[Tang dynasty|Tang]] and [[Song dynasty|Song]] dynasty coins, and [[commodity money]], such as cloth ({{Korean|\ud3ec\ud654|\u5e03\u8ca8|labels=no}}).<ref name=\"\uc6d0\uc720\ud55c\">{{cite web |last1=\uc6d0\uc720\ud55c |script-title=ko:\ucca0\uc804(\u9435\u9322) |url=http://encykorea.aks.ac.kr/Contents/Item/E0056169 |website=Encyclopedia of Korean Culture |publisher=Academy of Korean Studies |accessdate=13 October 2019 |language=ko}}</ref> Goryeo did not have a unified legal currency, and each region, ruled by the quasi-independent ''hojok'' ({{Korean|\ud638\uc871|\u8c6a\u65cf|labels=no}}) regional lords,{{sfn|Kim|2012|p=122}} used a different currency.<ref name=\"\uc6d0\uc720\ud55c\" />\n\nFollowing the [[Khitan people|Khitan]] destruction of the kingdom of [[Balhae]], which Goryeo had considered a country of kinship, [[Taejo of Goryeo]] proclaimed a ban on the circulation of all coins in 942.{{sfn|Jun|2014|pp=261\u2013262}} This was to sanction trade with the hated Khitans, who used metallic money, and protect Goryeo's metal reserves.{{sfn|Jun|2014|pp=261\u2013262}}{{sfn|Jun|2014|p=276}} In addition, Goryeo prepared itself for a conflict with the Khitan Empire.{{sfn|Kim|2012|pp=141\u2013142}}{{sfn|Lee|1984|p=125}} Taejo's prohibition in 942 indicates that, to some degree, coins had been circulating in Goryeo.{{sfn|Jun|2014|p=269}} Following the prohibition, rice and cloth were the [[medium of exchange]].{{sfn|Jun|2014|p=262}} Likewise, cloth was the medium of exchange for everyday transactions in the [[Liao dynasty]] and [[Jin dynasty (1115\u20131234)|Jin dynasty]].{{sfn|Jun|2014|p=268}} During this period in Goryeo, agriculture achieved high productivity and living standards improved; rice and textile production enabled Goryeo to increase its military strength.{{sfn|Jun|2014|p=262}} The ban on coins lasted until 996,{{sfn|Jun|2014|p=262}} three years after Goryeo had resumed diplomatic relations with the Liao dynasty.{{sfn|Jun|2014|p=270}}\n\nIn 996, [[Seongjong of Goryeo]] minted iron coins to trade with the Khitans, who used iron coins.{{sfn|Jun|2014|pp=270\u2013271}} The coins may have been issued to promote centralization.<ref name=\"\uc6d0\uc720\ud55c\" /> As far as can be established, the iron coins were not inscribed.{{sfn|Jun|2014|p=271}} The government made many efforts to promote the use of coins instead of commodity money;<ref name=\"History Net\">{{cite web |script-title=ko:\ud654\ud3d0\uc758 \uc0ac\uc6a9 |url=http://contents.history.go.kr/front/hm/view.do?treeId=010402&tabId=03&levelId=hm_059_0040 |website=History Net |publisher=National Institute of Korean History |accessdate=4 November 2019 |language=ko}}</ref> in 997, [[Mokjong of Goryeo]] prohibited the monetary use of hemp cloth,<ref name=\"Lee\">{{cite web |last1=Lee |first1=Hun-Chang |script-title=ko:\uace0\ub824\uc2dc\ub300 \uc740\ud654\u00b7\uc9c0\ud3d0\uc758 \uc81c\ud55c\uc801 \uc720\ud1b5 |url=http://contents.history.go.kr/front/km/view.do?levelId=km_008_0030_0010_0040 |website=History Net |publisher=National Institute of Korean History |accessdate=4 November 2019 |language=ko}}</ref> which, at the time, was the most widely used currency for everyday transactions.<ref name=\"History Net\" /> However, due to opposition, including from the nobility,<ref name=\"\uc6d0\uc720\ud55c\" /> the government repealed the prohibition and shifted its policy in 1002: the distribution of the coins was stopped and the public was allowed to use any currency.<ref name=\"Lee\" /><ref name=\"\uae40\uc7ac\uba85\">{{cite web |last1=\uae40\uc7ac\uba85 |script-title=ko:\uac74\uc6d0\uc911\ubcf4(\u4e7e\u5143\u91cd\u5bf6) |url=http://encykorea.aks.ac.kr/Contents/Index?contents_id=E0002015 |website=Encyclopedia of Korean Culture |publisher=Academy of Korean Studies |accessdate=15 October 2019 |language=ko}}</ref> Meanwhile, coins continued to be used at tea and wine shops (\u8336\u9152\u5e97) and restaurants.<ref name=\"\uc6d0\uc720\ud55c\" /><ref name=\"Lee\" /><ref name=\"\uae40\uc7ac\uba85\" />\n\nThe \"''Geonwon Jungbo''\", an iron coin inscribed with ''Geonwon Jungbo'' ({{Korean|\uac74\uc6d0\uc911\ubcf4|\u4e7e\u5143\u91cd\u5bf6|labels=no}}) on one side and ''Dongguk'' ({{Korean|\ub3d9\uad6d|\u6771\u570b|labels=no}}) on the other side, was excavated from a Goryeo tomb in the vicinity of [[Kaesong]], the capital of Goryeo, in the early 1910s; it was unearthed along with bronze ''Geonwon Jungbo'', ''Dongguk Tongbo'', and ''Dongguk Jungbo'' coins.<ref name=\"\uae40\uc7ac\uba85\" /><ref name=\"\uac74\uc6d0\uc911\ubcf4\">{{cite web |script-title=ko:\uac74\uc6d0\uc911\ubcf4 |url=http://contents.history.go.kr/front/ti/view.do?treeId=04013&levelId=ti_013_0150 |website=History Net |publisher=National Institute of Korean History |accessdate=15 October 2019 |language=ko}}</ref> However, its relation to Goryeo's iron coins minted in 996 is controversial.{{sfn|Boling|1988|p=1}} Gary Ashkenazy of \"Primal Trek\" says that the ''Geonwon Jungbo'' is not mentioned in Korean historical sources and was not cataloged until 1938 in the {{Nihongo| |\u6771\u4e9e\u9322\u5fd7|T\u014da senshi}} by Masahiro Okudaira, in which it is attributed to Goryeo.<ref name=\"Ashkenazy\">{{cite web |last1=Ashkenazy |first1=Gary |title=Korean Coins |url=http://primaltrek.com/koreancoins.html |website=Primal Trek |accessdate=16 October 2019 |language=en}}</ref>\n\nIn Korea, the ''Geonwon Jungbo'' is considered a Goryeo coin.<ref name=\"\uc6d0\uc720\ud55c\" /><ref name=\"\uae40\uc7ac\uba85\" /><ref name=\"\uac74\uc6d0\uc911\ubcf4\" /> The original coin, called the ''Qianyuan zhongbao'' in Chinese, dates to 759 during the Tang dynasty; the ''Geonwon Jungbo'', in contrast, is inscribed with ''Dongguk'' on the [[Obverse and reverse|reverse]].{{sfn|Jun|2014|p=271}} ''Dongguk'' was one of Goryeo's many names, along with ''Samhan'', ''Haedong'', ''Dongbang'', and ''Cheonggu''.{{sfn|Breuker|2010|pp=36\u201337}} According to Jun Seong Ho of the [[Academy of Korean Studies]]: \"Since cast coins cannot be altered, the coin cannot have been recast preserving the Tang inscription. Most probably, the coin was a heavy denomination cast by the [Goryeo] mint in the late tenth century.\"{{sfn|Jun|2014|p=271}} Furthermore, Goryeo and Tang coins have a different metal composition.{{sfn|Jun|2014|p=271}}\n\nIn China, the ''Geonwon Jungbo'' is viewed as a Goryeo coin or a Balhae coin.<ref name=\"\u738b\u7956\u8fdc\">{{cite web |last1=\u738b\u7956\u8fdc |script-title=zh:\u4e7e\u5143\u91cd\u5b9d\u80cc\u4e1c\u56fd |url=http://www.cssn.cn/sjs/sjs_hqzs/201709/t20170919_3644954.shtml |website=Chinese Social Sciences Net |accessdate=15 October 2019 |language=zh |date=19 September 2017}}</ref> The \"Goryeo coin\" viewpoint is represented by the ''T\u014da senshi'', published in 1938.<ref name=\"\u738b\u7956\u8fdc\" /> Wang Zuyuan, a proponent of the more recent \"Balhae coin\" viewpoint, says that Balhae always had close relations with and was strongly supported politically, economically, culturally, and militarily by the Tang dynasty; therefore, he concludes that Balhae, also known as \"''Haidong Shengguo''\" (\u6d77\u6771\u76db\u570b), minted the ''Geonwon Jungbo'' to show its loyalty to the Tang dynasty during the reign of [[Emperor Suzong of Tang|Emperor Suzong]] ({{reign|756|762}}).<ref name=\"\u738b\u7956\u8fdc\" /> However, Balhae coins have not been excavated.{{sfn|Kim|2008|p=304}}<ref>{{cite web |last1=\u9676\u77ed\u623f |script-title=zh:\u53e4\u6e24\u6d77\u56fd\u662f\u5426\u53d1\u884c\u94f8\u5e01?\u51fa\u571f\u5f00\u6cf0\u5143\u5b9d\u6216\u4e3a\u8236\u6765\u54c1 |url=http://www.chinanews.com/cul/2014/10-07/6651652.shtml |website=chinanews.com |publisher=\u5e7f\u5dde\u65e5\u62a5 |accessdate=22 October 2019 |language=zh}}</ref> Alexander Alexeyvich Kim says, \"One of the arguments the Chinese frequently use when they describe [Balhae] as 'provincial power of the Tang Empire' is the absence of [Balhae] coins.\"{{sfn|Kim|2008|p=304}} Russian archaeologists argue that Balhae may have used foreign currency, as many independent and developed states did.{{sfn|Kim|2008|p=304}}\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Inscription !! [[Hangul]] !! [[McCune\u2013Reischauer]] !! [[Revised Romanisation]] !! Image \n|- \n| \u4e7e\u5143\u91cd\u5bf6{{efn|In the modern era these cash coins are mostly unearthed in the Chinese province of [[Liaoning]] and [[North Korea]]. Some of them being unearthed in the city of [[Kaiyuan, Liaoning]].<ref name=\"BaiduNumismatics2011\">{{cite web|url= https://wk.baidu.com/view/254c43c5f705cc17552709d2?pcf=2|title= 2011\u5e74\u4e2d\u56fd\u94b1\u5e01\u5b66\u7814\u7a76\u7efc\u8ff0_\u56fe\u6587_\u767e\u5ea6\u6587\u5e93.|date=22 January 2014|accessdate=4 October 2019|work= A Summary of the Research on Chinese Numismatic Studies in 2011 (2011\u5e74\u4e2d\u56fd\u94b1\u5e01\u5b66\u7814\u7a76\u7efc\u8ff0)|publisher= [[Baidu]]|language=zh-cn}}</ref> The iron cash coins are more commonly found than the bronze ones. Currently only 10 pieces of the ''Geonwon Jungbo'' are known to exist making it an extremely valued object among [[East Asia]]n coin collectors.<ref name=\"SOUC201205021\">{{cite web|url= http://mall.cnki.net/magazine/article/SOUC201205021.htm|title= \"\u4e7e\u5143\u91cd\u5b9d\u00b7\u4e1c\u56fd\"\u94b1\u662f\u9ad8\u4e3d\u94b1\u5417?.|date=2 May 2012|accessdate=4 October 2019|work= mall.cnki.net/magazine/|language=zh-cn}}</ref>}}<br>\u6771\u570b || \uac74\uc6d0\uc911\ubcf4<br>\ub3d9\uad6d || ''K\u014fnw\u014fn Chungbo''<br>''Tongguk'' || ''Geonwon Jungbo''<br>''Dongguk'' || \n|}\n\n=== Middle period ===\nGoryeo issued new currencies during the reign of [[Sukjong of Goryeo]] ({{reign|1095|1105}}) based on proposals by the Buddhist monk [[Uichon]] and the military officer [[Yun Gwan]].<ref name=\"\ud45c\uc815\ud6c8\">{{cite web |last1=\ud45c\uc815\ud6c8 |script-title=ko:\uc758\ucc9c |url=https://terms.naver.com/entry.nhn?cid=59015&docId=3572347&categoryId=59015 |website=Naver Encyclopedia of Knowledge |accessdate=14 November 2019 |language=ko}}</ref> Uichon, who was a younger brother of Sukjong, argued for the implementation of a monetary economy, having experienced its convenience and efficiency in the [[Song dynasty]].<ref name=\"\ud45c\uc815\ud6c8\" /> Moreover, his proposed reform was intended to centralize the commerce and economy, which were dominated by the nobility.<ref name=\"\ud45c\uc815\ud6c8\" /> Uichon established a mint bureau in 1097;{{sfn|Jun|2014|p=270}} coins, named after [[Names of Korea#Sobriquets of Korea|sobriquets of Goryeo]], such as the ''Dongguk Tongbo'', ''Samhan Tongbo'', and ''Haedong Tongbo'' were subsequently minted and circulated. Beginning in 1101, a uniquely shaped silver currency called the ''\u016dnby\u014fng'' ({{Korean|\uc740\ubcd1|\u9280\u7501|labels=no}}), meaning \"silver vase\" in [[Korean language|Korean]], was cast and circulated.<ref name=\"\ubbfc\ubcd1\ud558\">{{cite web |last1=\ubbfc\ubcd1\ud558 |script-title=ko:\uc740\ubcd1(\u9280\u7501) |url=http://encykorea.aks.ac.kr/Contents/Item/E0042821 |website=Encyclopedia of Korean Culture |publisher=Academy of Korean Studies |accessdate=28 November 2019 |language=ko}}</ref>\n\nGoryeo bronze coins resembled standard East Asian coins of the time, but differed in that they were inscribed with a national name instead of an [[Regnal year|era name]].{{sfn|Jun|2014|pp=271\u2013272}} Sukjong actively promoted the use of coins.<ref name=\"History Net\" /> After a five-year delay due to opposition,<ref name=\"\uae40\ub3d9\ucca0\" /> 15,000 ''[[String of cash coins (currency unit)|gwan]]'' (or 15 million pieces) of the ''Haedong Tongbo'' were minted in 1102.<ref name=\"Lee\" />{{sfn|Boling|1988|p=1}}<ref name=\"\ubbfc\ubcd1\ud558\" /> Goryeo had circulated coins in the past, but this was the first full-scale circulation.<ref name=\"\ud45c\uc815\ud6c8\" /> The ''Sikhwaji'' ({{Korean|\uc2dd\ud654\uc9c0|\u98df\u8ca8\u5fd7|labels=no|lit=''Treatise on Food and Money''}}) in the ''[[History of Goryeo]]'' says: \"There is nothing more important than coinage, which may benefit our country and enrich the people ... It is only now that we have issued decrees about the minting of metal coinage.\"<ref name=\"History Net 2\">{{cite web |title=Korean Currency |url=http://contents.history.go.kr/front/eng/tz/view.do?levelId=tz_b25 |website=History Net |publisher=National Institute of Korean History |accessdate=7 December 2019 |language=en}}</ref> To promote their use, the newly minted coins were distributed to government officials and soldiers, and new shops were installed in the capital; in 1104, the states and prefectures were ordered to open new wine shops and restaurants.<ref name=\"Lee\" /> Sukjong died in 1105. In the following year, his monetary policy was met with stiff resistance from officials in both the central and provincial governments.<ref name=\"Lee\" /> Despite the opposition, [[Yejong of Goryeo]] doubled down on Sukjong's monetary policy in 1112.<ref name=\"Lee\" /> However, coins ultimately failed to gain widespread use in Goryeo.<ref name=\"Lee\" /><ref name=\"History Net 2\" /> Silver currency, on the other hand, was used continuously until the end of the dynasty.<ref name=\"Lee\" /> Xu Jing, a Song dynasty envoy who visited Goryeo in 1123, observed the use of the ''\u016dnby\u014fng'', but not coins, as a currency.<ref name=\"Lee\" />\n\nThe ''\u016dnby\u014fng'' \"silver vase\", popularly called the ''hwalgu'' ({{Korean|\ud65c\uad6c|\u95ca\u53e3|labels=no}}) for its broad mouth,{{sfn|Ledyard|1995|p=295}} was imprinted with a government seal and first issued in 1101.<ref name=\"Lee\" />{{sfn|Jun|2014|p=273}} It was made with one ''[[Korean units of measurement#Weight|geun]]'' ({{Korean|\uadfc|\u65a4|labels=no}}) of silver and designed to resemble the [[Cartography|cartographic]] outline of the Korean Peninsula.<ref name=\"\ubbfc\ubcd1\ud558\" />{{sfn|Ledyard|1995|p=240}} The ''\u016dnby\u014fng'' was made because of the illegal manufacture of silver currency;<ref name=\"Lee\" /> all other silver currencies were prohibited by the government.{{sfn|Jun|2014|p=273}} As a stable, standardized currency, the ''\u016dnby\u014fng'' was used throughout the kingdom in both public finance and private trade; it was also used to pay taxes.{{sfn|Jun|2014|p=273}} The ''\u016dnby\u014fng'' was widely used as a currency by the nobility, whereas grain and cloth were used by the common people.{{sfn|Kim|2012|p=138}} Furthermore, the ''\u016dnby\u014fng'' was used mainly in large transactions.<ref name=\"Lee\" />{{sfn|Ledyard|1995|p=240}} According to Jun Seong Ho: \"For roughly 150 years from the early twelfth to the mid thirteenth century, silver was the main currency of [Goryeo].\"{{sfn|Jun|2014|p=273}} Silver had been used as a currency before the ''\u016dnby\u014fng'' was made.<ref name=\"Lee\" /> Korean silver metallurgy was advanced, and Koreans exported silver, possibly in the form of [[ingot]]s, to the Jurchens in the mid 10th century;{{sfn|Jun|2014|p=269}} Korean silver metallurgy was exported to the Jurchens in 1102.{{sfn|Jun|2014|p=273}} The ''\u016dnby\u014fng'' remained the only standardized silver currency in [[East Asia]] until the 16th century with the start of a silver mining boom in Japan,{{sfn|Jun|2014|p=275}} enabled by the introduction of [[cupellation]] from Korea in 1533.<ref>{{cite web |title=Refining Silver: \"Haifuki Cupellation Method\" |url=https://ginzan.city.ohda.lg.jp/wh/en/technology/haifuki.html |website=Iwami Ginzan World Heritage Center |publisher=Shimane Prefectural Government |accessdate=29 December 2019 |language=en}}</ref>{{sfn|Carlson|2012|p=157}}\n\nGoryeo was a period of flourishing commerce, and Goryeo actively engaged in commercial activity with the Song dynasty during the 11th and 12th centuries.{{sfn|Lee|2017|p=52}} Song dynasty coins circulated in many parts of Asia.<ref name=\"\uae40\ub3d9\ucca0\" /> Goryeo, too, imported coins from the Song dynasty; more Song dynasty coins have been excavated than Goryeo coins in Korea.<ref name=\"Lee\" /> However, they were not necessarily used as a currency, but rather as a [[Offering (Buddhism)|religious offering]] or [[grave good]].<ref name=\"Lee\" /> In 1199, the Song government prohibited the export of coins to Goryeo and Japan.<ref name=\"\uae40\ub3d9\ucca0\" /><ref name=\"Lee\" />\n\n=== Late period ===\nGoryeo experienced a silver famine in the 13th century due to [[Mongol invasions of Goryeo|Mongol invasions]].{{sfn|Jun|2014|p=274}}{{sfn|Lee|2017|p=64}} By the late 13th century, Goryeo was depleted of most of its silver by the [[Yuan dynasty]].{{sfn|Jun|2014|p=274}} Beginning with the reign of [[Chungnyeol of Goryeo]], the Yuan dynasty assumed control of Goryeo's monetary system and imposed its paper money; thus, Goryeo lost its monetary sovereignty.{{sfn|Jun|2014|pp=274\u2013275}} The destabilizing introduction of a new currency demonetized the economy.{{sfn|Jun|2014|p=276}}\n\nThe shortage of silver in Goryeo led to the [[debasement]] and [[Counterfeit money|counterfeiting]] of silver currency; the Goryeo government experienced problems with the ''\u016dnby\u014fng''.<ref name=\"Lee\" /> Goryeo's \"Bureau of Capital City Markets\" ({{Korean|\uacbd\uc2dc\uc11c|\u4eac\u5e02\u7f72|labels=no}}) adjusted the value of the ''\u016dnby\u014fng'' annually according to the harvest; in 1282, the value of one ''\u016dnby\u014fng'' was set at 15 to 16 ''[[Korean units of measurement#Volume|seok]]'' ({{Korean|\uc11d|\u77f3|labels=no}}) of rice in the capital and 18 to 19 ''seok'' of rice in the provinces.<ref name=\"Lee\" /><ref name=\"Bank of Korea\">{{cite web |last1=\uc624\uacbd\uc12d |script-title=ko:\ub3c5\ud2b9\ud55c \ud615\ud0dc\ub97c \uc9c0\ub2cc \uc740\ubcd1(\u9280\u7501)\ud654\ud3d0 |url=https://www.bok.or.kr/portal/bbs/P0000547/view.do?nttId=17770&menuNo=200387 |website=[[Bank of Korea]] |accessdate=3 October 2019 |language=ko}}</ref> The high value of the ''\u016dnby\u014fng'' led to the use of silver [[ingot]]s called \"''swae\u016dn''\" ({{Korean|\uc1c4\uc740|\u788e\u9280|labels=no|lit=broken silver}}) as a currency, which were valued based on weight.<ref name=\"Lee\" /> However, they were prohibited in 1287 because of the appearance of counterfeits mixed with copper.<ref name=\"Lee\" /><ref name=\"\uace0\ub824\uc0ac\">{{cite web |title=\uc740\uacfc \ub3d9\uc744 \uc11e\uc5b4 \uc8fc\uc870\ud558\ub294 \uc77c\uc744 \uae08\uc9c0\ud558\ub2e4 |url=http://db.history.go.kr/KOREA/item/level.do?itemId=kr&bookId=%E5%BF%97&types=r#detail/kr_079r_0010_0030_0100 |website=Korean History Database |publisher=National Institute of Korean History |accessdate=15 February 2020 |language=ko}}</ref> The ''\u016dnby\u014fng'' was also counterfeited, and had been since its inception; as the ''\u016dnby\u014fng'' became increasingly debased with copper,{{efn|The ''\u016dnby\u014fng'' was originally composed of 80% silver and 20% copper.{{sfn|Jun|2014|p=273}}}} its value decreased, and by 1328 the value of one ''\u016dnby\u014fng'' of the highest quality dropped to 10 bolts of cloth.<ref name=\"Lee\" /> In 1331, the Goryeo government abolished the ''\u016dnby\u014fng'' and replaced it with the miniaturized \"''so \u016dnby\u014fng''\" ({{Korean|\uc18c\uc740\ubcd1|\u5c0f\u9280\u7501|labels=no|lit=small ''\u016dnby\u014fng''}}), which was valued at 15 bolts of cloth.{{sfn|Jun|2014|pp=275\u2013276}}\n\nYuan paper money was introduced to Goryeo in 1270.<ref name=\"Lee\" /> In 1287, the Yuan dynasty decreed the use of the ''Zhiyuan baochao'' ({{Korean|\uc9c0\uc6d0\ubcf4\ucd08|\u81f3\u5143\u5bf6\u9214|labels=no}}) and ''Zhongtong baochao'' ({{Korean|\uc911\ud1b5\ubcf4\ucd08|\u4e2d\u7d71\u5bf6\u9214|labels=no}}) in Goryeo.<ref name=\"Lee\" /><ref name=\"\uace0\ub824\uc0ac\" /> Approximately 100,000 ''jeong'' ({{Korean|\uc815|\u9320|labels=no}}) of ''baochao'' were circulated in Goryeo.<ref name=\"Lee\" /> The ''baochao'' was used extensively in trade with the Yuan dynasty.<ref name=\"Lee\" /> During its [[Mongol invasions of Japan|invasions of Japan]], the Yuan dynasty paid for ships and soldiers in Goryeo with ''baochao'' paper money.<ref name=\"Lee\" /> According to Hun-Chang Lee of [[Korea University]]'s Department of Economics, the inflow of paper currency and outflow of silver currency harmed the development of currency in Korea.<ref name=\"Lee\" /> Meanwhile, the Yuan dynasty exported large quantities of coin to Japan, which had not minted its own coins since the late 10th century.<ref name=\"Lee\" />{{sfn|Jun|2014|p=274}} In the ''Sinan'' shipwreck of 1323, approximately 28 tons of coin were being transported by ship from China to Japan before sinking off the coast of the Korean Peninsula.{{sfn|von Glahn|2014|p=272}}\n\nYuan paper money was abolished in 1356 with Goryeo's independence from the Yuan dynasty.<ref name=\"Lee\" /> Instead, silver currency and hemp cloth stamped with a government seal were used as currencies.<ref name=\"Lee\" /> During the end of the Goryeo period, the monetary system was in a state of disarray, and various currencies were debased.<ref name=\"\uad8c\uc778\ud601\">{{cite web |last1=\uad8c\uc778\ud601 |script-title=ko:\uc800\ud654(\u696e\u8ca8) |url=https://encykorea.aks.ac.kr/Contents/Item/E0049125 |website=Encyclopedia of Korean Culture |publisher=Academy of Korean Studies |accessdate=1 April 2020 |language=ko}}</ref> Thus, in 1391, the Korean government introduced a new monetary system, consisting of both metallic currency ({{Korean|\uc804\ud654|\u9322\u8ca8|Jeonhwa|labels=no}}) and paper currency ({{Korean|\uc800\ud654|\u696e\u8ca8|Jeohwa|labels=no}}).<ref name=\"\uad8c\uc778\ud601\" /> The Goryeo dynasty transitioned into the [[Joseon|Joseon dynasty]] in 1392. ''Jeohwa'' paper money continued to be used during the early Joseon period.<ref name=\"\uad8c\uc778\ud601\" /> Meanwhile, the ''\u016dnby\u014fng'' finally came to an end in 1408 after 300 years.<ref name=\"\uc624\uacbd\uc12d\" /> A specimen of the miniaturized \"''so \u016dnby\u014fng''\", presumably dating to the late Goryeo period, has been discovered and currently resides in the [[Bank of Korea Money Museum]], but a specimen of the larger original ''\u016dnby\u014fng'' has yet to be found.<ref name=\"\uc624\uacbd\uc12d\" />\n\n== List of Goryeo cash coins by inscription ==\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Inscription !! [[Hangul]] !! [[McCune\u2013Reischauer]] !! [[Revised Romanisation]] !! [[Chinese script styles|Scripts]] !! Date of casting !! Diameter<br>(in millimeter) !! Weight<br>(in grams) !! Image\n|- \n| \u6771\u570b\u901a\u5bf6 || \ub3d9\uad6d\ud1b5\ubcf4 || Dong kuk T'ong Bo || Dong Guk Tong Bo || [[Seal script]] (\u7bc6\u66f8), [[Clerical script]] (\u96b8\u